<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-23 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Argentine Allegation of Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Iran today strongly rejected
the allegation raised by an Argentine official that Tehran was
possibly behind a terrorist bombing in Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi urged the Argentine
government to "watch for the conspiracies now jeopardizing the
interests of Iran and Argentina."
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said an anti-Iran propaganda campaign has been
launched by certain circles in Argentina to please the Zionist
regime (Israel).
</P>
<P>
Media reports said an Argentine official stated Saturday that
Argentina was examining the evidences to determine if Iran had
been involved in the bomb blast of a Jewish center in Buenos Aires
on July 18, 1994, which killed some 88 people and injured 159
others.
</P>
<P>
Manouchehr Motamer, an Iranian national, offered some
information to the Argentine judicial authorities that four
Iranian diplomats were involved in the bomb blast. However,
during the past three years no enough evidence was found to prove
Iran's involvement in the bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that the propaganda campaign against Iran aimed
to make up for the political setbacks suffered by Israel and the
United States at the recent Doha regional economic conference and
in the so-called Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. which failed to array its European allies
against Iran has now launched an anti-Iran propaganda campaign
in Argentina, adding that the U.S. and Israel have embarked on a
new wave of propaganda campaign against Iran to divert the
public opinion from their repeated defeats in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The investigations launched by the Argentine government over
the past three years have indicated that Iran had not been
involved in the bomb blast, he said.
</P>
<P>
Any reference to the baseless allegation raised by an Iranian
fugitive with records of embezzlement and collaboration with the
U.S. intelligence service and who has been condemned by a
U.S. court on charge of shop-lifting is a suspicious move, he
added.
</P>
<P>
He warned the argentine officials to keep close eyes on the
conspiracy which is aimed at damaging the interests of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
One week ago, Iran and the European Union has resolved their
seven-month-long diplomatic row which was triggered by a Berlin
court verdict accusing Tehran of sponsoring terrorist
assassination of four Iranian Kurdish leaders in Berlin in
1992. Now all 15 EU countries' envoys have returned to Tehran
after Iran reached a compromise with the EU on November 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
