<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly Half Nigerians in Poverty, Says Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian, once boasting an
annual gross national product of 1,000 U.S. Dollars per capita at
the oil boom in the 70s, is facing the hard fact that nearly half
of its people are living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the outcome of a nationwide consumer survey
conducted by the Federal Office of Statistics (FOS), which covers
the period between April 1996 and March 1997.
</P>
<P>
Taking poverty level as 657.69 Naira (one U.S. Dollars equals
to about 83 Naira currently) which is two-thirds of the weighted
mean per capita monthly expenditure, FOS found that 42.9 percent
of the total urban households are below the poverty line. The
figure for the rural area is 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Those below poverty line in the northeastern zone account for
55.9 percent of the total households sampled in the north, while
37.3 percent was below poverty line in the total households in
the southeastern zone.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, which sampled 13,801 households
nationwide, more than 75 percent of their monthly income is spent
on household needs.
</P>
<P>
Of the average income of 5,383 Naira, 4,058 Naira goes to such
basic household needs as hood, accommodation, fuel and light,
drinks and tobacco, household goods, transport, clothing and
other essential items.
</P>
<P>
In its preliminary report of the National Consumer Survey, FOS
said household income per month is higher in the south and
central zones than in the northern zone.
</P>
<P>
The highest income (7,213 Naira) is recorded in the
southeastern zone, the country's oil production base, while the
lowest comes from the northwest, where most people are engaged in
farming.
</P>
<P>
People in the two zones, consequently, spend the most and the
least on household items, which stands at 5,194 and 2,941 Naira
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The effect of urbanization reflects in the income pattern.
</P>
<P>
Whereas the income level of an average urban dweller is 6,490
Naira, that of rural dweller is 5,066 Naira.
</P>
<P>
The household expenditure under survey does not take into
account school fees and medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
The survey does not reveal much difference in the size of
households in urban and rural areas. Whereas the urban households
have averagely 4.4 members, the rural ones have that of 4.7.
</P>
<P>
Of the 13,801 households sampled, 1,863 or 13.5 percent are
headed by females, mainly in the southern and central zones.
</P>
<P>
The national average age of the head of the household is 44.6
years, 45 years for the rural area and 43.5 for the urban area.
Female heads of households have an average age of 48 years, while
their male counterparts recorded an average of 44 years.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, west and southeast zones have a slightly higher
average for the age of the head of households than the other
regions. The report attributes the differences to early marriage
in some parts of the country than in others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
