<HEADLINE> Mongolia Speeds up Highway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, November 23 (Xinhua) -- As part of the efforts to
link with Asia's highway networks in the 21st century, Mongolia is
accelerating the construction program to expand its highway system
north to Russia and east to China.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian Infrastructure Development Ministry said Saturday
that the extension project is scheduled to be completed in 1999,
costing a total of 23.3 million U.S. dollars, which will be
provided by the Asian Development Bank on favorable terms.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian government has recently decided to build another
1,000-kilometer-long highway which starts from Ulan Bator, runs
through Ondorhaan and cross Mongolia's giant oil field in the
Tamsagbulag area of Dornod province to finally reach the
Mongolia-China border.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion, the new highway will help promote the
Sino-Mongolian trade and speed up the economic development in the
eastern part of Mongolia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
