<HEADLINE> France Separates Names of Vichy Judges from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 23 (Xinhua) -- France will separate for the
first time in the year-book of magistrature the names of the
judges who served the Vichy regime under Marshal Philippe Petain
from those who joined resistance against German occupation, said
the daily Le Monde today.
</P>
<P>
The names of the nine judges, who were cited at the order of
the nation in the year-book, were mixed on the same page in 34
previous editions published since the end of the war.
</P>
<P>
Among the nine judges, four were honored by Petain after being
killed by resistance fighters, while five others were killed by
Germans after joining resistance movement or being deported to
Nazi concentration camps. They were honored at the order of the
nation after the liberation of France on August 9, 1944.
</P>
<P>
The decision to separate these names into two pages was made by
the Minister of Justice Elisabeth Guigou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
