<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-23 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Rules Out Dialog With Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today ruled out the possibility of holding any dialog with the
terrorists that have been fighting a five-year war against his
secular government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the opening of the Nubia Museum in the
Upper Egyptian city of Aswan, the president said that he has
learned from the past and from the dialog with the terrorists in
the 1980s, during the rule of late president Anwar Sadat, that this
kind of approach only makes the terrorists get stronger.
</P>
<P>
Aswan, about 800 kilometers south of Cairo, is about 300
kilometers down from Luxor, which on Monday witnessed a bloodbath
when Islamic militants gunned down 62 people.
</P>
<P>
"The matter would be like a dialog with the blind and the
deaf," Mubarak said, adding that any dialog with the terrorists
would be useless now that they have resorted to arms.
</P>
<P>
The government has rejected several ceasefire calls made since
July by some jailed leaders of Jihad and the Gamaa Islamiya,
Egypt's ultra-radical groups.
</P>
<P>
It has consistently rejected any talks with the militants with
one exception, which took place in 1993 when former Interior
Minister Mohamed Abdel-Halim Moussa conducted negotiations with
the militant groups via a mediation committee. The negotiations
proved unsuccessful and cost Moussa his job.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Egypt is doing its best to guarantee
the safety of tourists to prevent the recurrence of such terrorist
attacks and called upon all countries to muster efforts to fight
this global ailment. But he declined to dislose the results of
investigations into the November 17 attack.
</P>
<P>
The six terrorists who carried out the attack on tourists in
front of Luxor's Hatshepsut Temple were all killed, according to
Egyptian Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Before addressing reporters, amid tight security, Mubarak, his
ministers and a host of world leaders were shown around the giant
60-million-Egyptian pound (nearly 18-million-U.S.-dollar) museum,
built on a rocky hilltop in Aswan.
</P>
<P>
Egypt opened the museum less than a week after the savage
massacre in Luxor to show the government's resolve to revive
tourism, a 3-billion-dollar-per-year industry for the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Before the incident, Aswan and Luxor, the two most brilliant
archeological pearls in Upper Egypt, had been largely free from
Islamic militant insurgency, which in the past five years has
claimed 1,300 lives.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, angered by the laxity of security at major tourist
sites, has sacked his interior minister. The new security chief
immediately revamped the security leaderships and vowed to
fight terrorists across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
