<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Starts Visit in Guiana One Year After Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 23 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today began a three-day visit to France's overseas department of
Guiana in the Amazon region of South America, one year after high
school students staged riots in its capital Cayenne.
</P>
<P>
Chirac is accompanied by the State Secretary for Overseas
Departments and Territories, Jean-Jack Queyranne, and the Minister
of National Education, Claude Allegre.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will send a message of hope to the youth of the overseas
department, who make up half of the local population, insisting on
the importance of Guiana for France and the will of the government
to develop the territory, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
The European space center for sending Ariane rockets is based
in Kourou, in Guiana.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will also meet with Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso on Tuesday in Saint-Georges at the Oyapock River
along the border between Guiana and Brazil. Immigration of
Brazilians into Guiana is expected to be the center of their
talks.
</P>
<P>
The visit took place after a government report said recently
that Guiana is faced with three crises: crisis of development,
crisis of political confidence and crisis of culture and identity.
</P>
<P>
Government officials suggested a plan to improve conditions of
public equipments and public services, to improve territorial
management and to control settlement of people in the territory.
</P>
<P>
Guiana is faced with a large number of immigrants mainly from
Brazil, Haiti and Surinam, while the local Creole community can no
longer absorb new-comers because of dense population rate
concentrated along the coast area of the territory.
</P>
<P>
The population of Guiana doubled over the past 20 years to
150,000, 20-30 percent of whom are illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Guiana's high school students rioted in November 1996 in
Cayenne to protest poor conditions in schools, which ended after
the government agreed to their demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Says U.N. Engagement With Iraq Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 23 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin said today that the United Nations engagement with Iraq to
continue their cooperation over disarmament inspection will be "a
beautiful success for Europe" if it moves to the end positively.
</P>
<P>
At the closing session of the congress of the French Socialist
Party held in Brest in west France, Jospin said that the United
States was "under the pain of finding itself isolated."
</P>
<P>
"Without yielding before Iraq and to its unacceptable rejection
of the U.N. resolutions, we passed from the risk of a conflict to
the possibility of a diplomatic solution,"said Jospin. 
