<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diarrhea Breaks out in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Severe diarrhoea has broken
out in the Somali capital Mogadishu, following the heavy rains
that hit southern Somalia for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
Doctors in Mogadishu said at least five children die everyday
for what is termed as "acute watery diarrhoea".
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the main Paediatric Hospital of Mogadishu which is
run by SOS-Austria said, more than 400 cases of acute diarrhoea
were registered in the out-patient department of the hospital
during the the past nine days.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Mohamed Ibrahim, administrator of the hospital, said an
average of 40 children, most of them under five, are being
received every 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
He added that 50 percent of the children are those deported
from the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, while other 20 percent are from
the flood-displaced families in the southern regions of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Eleven children have died of diarrhoea in SOS hospital in the
past three days, among whom were three male infants who died as
they arrived in the hospital, he said, adding that other
considerable number of children affected by the disease die
before making to the hospitals every day.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rains that hit the capital have worsened the already
poor sanitation situation thus spreading the contagious diseases.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Mohamed Mohamud Fuje from Dr Hassan Jiis Memorial Hospital
told the press that lack of public awareness and water
chlorination program in the city have also contributed to the
speedy spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
"Many people do not even know what to do and where to go when
they are hit by the diarrhoea and their body resistance is very
weak," Fuje said.
</P>
<P>
Aid agencies have focused only on the flood-affected regions
of southern Somalia, and "they don't consider Mogadishu as a
flood-affected area," he added.
</P>
<P>
The huge influx of diarrhoea victims have stormed the SOS
hospital which has only 120 beds. The six qualified doctors and
14 nurses are all attending the patients during the hectic hour
of the day today.
</P>
<P>
Parents of the young patients who were stranded in the
hospital gardens with infusions hanging on with their children
under the trees, asked for more infusions and antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
"We used to spend maximum 100 infusions per day, and now are
exceeding 600 pieces," said Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Rahma Hassan, 35 and a mother of four children under five who
were all affected by the diarrhoea, said three of her children
have recovered while one more still remained in the hospital
gardens.
</P>
<P>
Rahma who is one of the deportee from Saudi Arabia, blamed the
change of tDiarrhoeahe weather and water for the cause of the
disease, saying, "In Saudi Arabia, my children drank clean water,
but here we're using non-chlorinated water brought on donkey
driven carts from open shallow well."
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people are deported from Saudi Arabia every week
as part of their campaign against illegal foreigners in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
