<HEADLINE> French FM to Start Visit to Middle East Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 23 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine will start a visit to Israel, the Palestinian territories
and Egypt from Monday, the first by the foreign minister since the
French Socialists came to power in June.
</P>
<P>
During his visit in Israel, Vedrine will encourage the Israeli
government to continue pursuing the Middle East peace process and
will express France's understanding of Israel's concern over
violence and terrorism, said French officials.
</P>
<P>
A French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman denied on Friday a report
by Israeli television that Vedrine will carry a message jointly
signed by French President Jacques Chirac, German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and British Prime Minister Tony Blair, blaming the
Israeli government for the impasse of the Middle East situation.
</P>
<P>
When he visits the Palestinian territories, Vedrine will ask
Palestinians to "move ahead" in the peace process inspite of the
difficulties they are faced with now.
</P>
<P>
He will also reaffirm France's support to the right of
self-determination of Palestinians and the possibility of creating
a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
During an informal meeting held on Thursday evening in
Luxembourg, the foreign ministers of 15 European Union countries
expressed their "growing concern" over the blockade of the peace
process in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
