<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monument Erected in Greece to Commemorate Killed Jews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Greek President Costis
Stephanopoulos today unveiled a monument in the northern Greek
city of Thessaloniki to commemorate the city's 50,000 Jews killed
by the Nazi occupation forces in concentration camps in eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the unveiling ceremony attended by government
officials from Greece, Israel, the U.S. and representatives of
Jewish communities from around the world, Stephanopoulos said that
the Greek people had not, all these years, forgotten the victims
of the Nazi barbarity.
</P>
<P>
For the Greek people, He said, the memory of the genocide of
the Jews would always hurt. He called on everyone to never again
allow evil to take root in the world.
</P>
<P>
In his message to the ceremony, Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis said that in honoring the memory of the Jews of
Thessaloniki and once again condemning the Nazi atrocities, they
might hope that the present and future generations would learn
from this bitter lesson.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. President Bill Clinton said in a message that
the Thessaloniki monument would stand as a reminder of the past
evil but also as an inspiration for future good.
</P>
<P>
The monument, which shows a tangle of human skeletons beneath a
burning menora, the candelabra used in Jewish worship, was crafted
by Yugoslav Jew sculptor Nador Gild, who created similar holocaust
memorials in Jerusalem, Belgrade and the Nazi concentration camp
Dachau.
</P>
<P>
Israel Saturday welcomed the Greek government's establishment
of such a monument. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
