<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin: Economic Drop Stopped in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Economic recession has stopped
for the first time over the period of reforms in Russia this year,
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a Russian-American forum of business elite held in Moscow
Chernomyrdin said that over the first 10 months of this year the
Russian GDP totalled 100.3 percent compared with last year's GDP,
production growth was up 1.6 percent and is expected to be up 1.8
percent by the end of the year, and annual inflation is expected
to be 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the premier, more than 75 percent of GDP came from
non-state companies. "Much has been said about whether our
privatization has gone right or wrong, but there has been no other
way for us," Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged mistakes had been made, but said that
privatization of big companies will be continued. Russia "intends
to do all it can to join the World Trade Organization by the end
of 1998," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
He meanwhile called on foreign investment in Russian economy,
stressing that the Russian economy will be unable to develop
without investments.
</P>
<P>
The first major Russian-American business forum, held in Moscow
on November 22-23, is the first meeting of such magnitude between
business elite representatives of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The topics of the forum are bilateral contacts, international
financial markets and prospects for regional and international
integration.
</P>
<P>
The forum was being attended by representatives of leading
Russian and American companies, banks and financial groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
