<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-23 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Strongly Denies Making Promise to Freeze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Countering local media
reports, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu vehemently
denied today having made any promise to the U.S. government over
freezing settlement construction.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that U.S President Bill Clinton told
former Israeli prime minister Shimon Peres Friday that Netanyahu
had committed to a time-out of settlement construction in the
West Bank. In his reaction, Netanyahu told today's weekly Cabinet
meeting that he had never made such statements or commitments to
freeze settlement construction.
</P>
<P>
A Cabinet statement quoted Netanyahu as saying Israel made no
promise on settlements, neither in his meeting with U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright in London nine days ago nor in the
meetings held in Washington by Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy with Palestinian negotiators early this month.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said Israel has made it clear that freezing
settlements is outside the bands of the agreement. He stressed
that if the Palestinian side wants Israel to further pull back
from the West Bank, it should make progress on living up to their
security commitments.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu today held extensive consultations with senior
ministers in the inner Cabinet Levy, Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai and Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky on
current security situation and the stalemated peace process.
</P>
<P>
Local television and newspapers reported today that during
Clinton's meeting with Peres, who is a leading architect of the
Israeli-Arab peace process, the U.S. president reportedly said it
is difficult to have faith in Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
In a public speech in the same day, Clinton called bluntly on
both Israeli and Palestinian sides to advance the peace process,
warning that "the window of progress will become smaller with
time."
</P>
<P>
In reaction to media reports on the Clinton-Peres meeting,
Israeli Prime Minister's Office today strongly denounced the
leaking of the meeting to the press by Peres' aides as
"shameful." The office said that no meeting has been arranged
between Peres and Netanyahu to allow the former to brief on his
talks with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, European Union (EU) special envoy Miguel Moratinos
held talks here today with senior Israeli officials to discuss
the EU initiative on formulating the so-called code of conduct
for the Israeli-Palestinian permanent talks which have not yet
begun.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos told Israel Radio that he believes an agreement on
the EU initiative will be signed by the end of the month. He said
neither sides are creating difficulty in formulating the code of
conduct, which calls on both sides to refrain from taking
unilateral steps.
</P>
<P>
The code also demanded both sides to promote security
cooperation in order to prevent further violence and terrorist
attacks. Specifically, the sides will set up a permanent security
council to deal with security issues.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos said he is working to finalize the remaining 10
percent of the code of conduct. Israel Radio reported that under
the code of conduct, Israel is not committing itself to freezing
settlements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side is reportedly opposed to the idea of
referring mutual disputes to the international community, a
position cited by Israel as proof that the Palestinians intend to
continue creating troubles for Israel in the international
arena. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
