<HEADLINE> Netanyahu's Senior Assistant Resigns over Likud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister's
office Director-General Avidor Lieberman has resigned over the
crisis in the ruling Likud party caused by a controversial party
convention on the internal election primaries.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Channel 2 Television reported today that the Prime
Minister's office has refused to comment on Lieberman's
resignation, who was widely considered Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's right-hand man and has been the focus figure in the
recent crisis.
</P>
<P>
Likud has been mired in the crisis since its central committee
decided on the November 12 convention to scrap the election
primary system, which has conferred upon the Likud high-ups
considerable advantage in the choice of the party's candidates for
the Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Likud's ministers and Knesset members, who hotly oppose the
decision and are critical of its proceedings, have demanded
Netanyahu to sack Lieberman for his "improper activities" during
the convention.
</P>
<P>
They charged that Lieberman had managed the Likud convention
via remote control and had his opponents clandestinely
videotaped at the event.
</P>
<P>
In response, Netanyahu decided Thursday to set up an inquiry
committee to probe all complaints regarding the convention and he
vowed that he would abide by any recommendation the committee
makes.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would not tolerate any impropriety in the
convention vote, but he also made it clear that there would be no
question of sacking Lieberman before the probe was carried out.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the report said that Likud central
committee will meet Monday to voice their opposition to
Netanyahu's another proposal to hold party's referendum on the
primary system, which may pave the way for the return of the
primaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
