<HEADLINE> World Court to Judge Bakassi Case Next June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Court of
Justice is expected to finalize next year the case of the Bakassi
peninsula over which both Nigeria and Cameroun claim ownership.
</P>
<P>
"The court has now fixed March for the hearing and judgement
will be delivered in June," Chief Michael Agbamuche, former
minister of justice, said today in the capital Abjua.
</P>
<P>
In his hand-over note, Agbamuche, who was sacked when the
cabinet was dissolved last Monday, said he got the confirmation
last week at a meeting with the president of the court during his
last official assignment as attorney-general of the federation at
the Hague.
</P>
<P>
Then his delegation and that from Cameroun went to the court
last week.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun have claimed territorial sovereignty over
the oil-rich Bakassi peninsula and repeated clashes have been
reported between soldiers of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have submitted the case to the world court in
the Hague for judgement. 
</P>
