<HEADLINE> Israeli MP Urges Withdrawal from S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 23 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli Member of the
Knesset (parliament) today urged the government to pull out the
Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) from South Lebanon, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the military conflicts occurred Saturday evening
and today in South Lebanon, Yossi Beilin, a Labor member of the
parliament, said in Tel Aviv that the latest developments there
again proved that the security zone does not protect the security
of north Israel.
</P>
<P>
Only after the IDF withdraws from South Lebanon, can real peace
be achieved between north Israel and South Lebanon, he added.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Israeli government and military to take positive
attitude in seeking agreements with the Lebanese side on the IDF
withdrawal from South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
According to the IDF, rockets fired from South Lebanon hit
several villages in the southern part of the security zone
Saturday evening which caused heavy damages to the villagers.
</P>
<P>
Israeli jet fighters bombed twice this morning some positions
of the Shiite Amal movement in South Lebanon in retaliation for
their shelling again earlier this morning of several villages in
the security zone, in which nine Lebanese civilians, including
four children, were killed.
</P>
<P>
The bombing led to more Katyusha shelling of the southern part
of the security zone and three of the shells landed within Israeli
territory, but caused no damage.
</P>
<P>
Micha Goldman, another Labor member of the parliament, today
visited the area hit by the Katyusha in north Israel. He urged
both the IDF and the Lebanese army to refrain from shelling each
other and solve the disputes through consultations.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent more blood shedding in South Lebanon,
Beilin formed on November 9 a movement to lobby for the IDF to
pull out from South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the 1,100-square-kilometer security zone in
South Lebanon in 1985 to protect its northern towns from across
the border attack. Since then, the IDF there have been facing
strong resistance from the Lebanese army, particularly from the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
