<HEADLINE> Arafat Urges US to Pressure Israel to Halt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat today urged the United
States to pressure Israel to halt its settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from India to Gaza, Arafat said that the
continuation of the Israeli settlement activities in the PNA
territories is a violation of the agreements signed between PNA
and Israel, according to the Palestinian Radio VOP.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the United states to pressure Israel to
implement the agreements reached by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nabil Abu Rdeineh, advisor to Arafat, said in Gaza
today that the latest positive change in the U.S. diplomatic
position began to be differentiated from the Israeli position,
and the U.S. should pressure the Israeli government to halt
settlement activities and implement the agreements.
</P>
<P>
Nabil's remarks were apparently related to U.S. President Bill
Clinton's Friday speech in Washington, in which Clinton called on
Israel and the PNA to intensively tackle the next set of issues to
move the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
Clinton Friday received the 1997 Man of Peace Award from a
foundation established in honor of the late Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin and his successor Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the receiving ceremony at the White House, Clinton
asked Israel and the PNA to speed up talks on the four-part agenda
that the U.S. identified in September: security cooperation, the
Israeli troops' required redeployment, a time-out of the
settlement activities, and moving to final-status peace talks.
</P>
<P>
But on the settlement issue, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu told his cabinet today that he has never promised to
Clinton that Israel is to halt settlement activities in the near
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
