<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Learn Democracy Through Self-Governance (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the view of civil affairs officials, who are in charge of
rural democracy, a complete system of farmers' self-governance
should consist of "four democracies."
</P>
<P>
Besides the democratic election (of the villagers' committee),
the other three democracies refer to democratic decision-making
(in village management), democratic management (of village
affairs) and democratic supervision (by the villagers over the
village leadership).
</P>
<P>
According to Li, the necessary measures to guarantee democratic
rights to these farmers' include formulating methods for the
election of villagers' committees, setting up a system of
villagers' council or villagers' congress, enacting a village
constitution and making public all village affairs.
</P>
<P>
Li went on to say that the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China, convened two months ago in Beijing, once
again showed the Party's determination to expand grassroots
democracy throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin said in the report to the Party
Congress that "expanding grassroots democracy and guaranteeing the
people's direct exercise of their democratic rights" represent the
"most widespread practice of socialist democracy".
</P>
<P>
"This assertion has lighted the way for the practice of
villagers' self-governance and the building of grassroots
democratic politics in the rural areas to advance into the next
century," Li said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in the coming year a dozen provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities would usher in a new round
of elections of villagers' committees.
</P>
<P>
"The civil affairs departments across the country will focus on
improving the legal system related to farmers' self-governance and
increasing the democracy and transparency in village management
after a democratic election," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
