<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Cracks Drug-Production Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Five suspected criminals have
been arrested for producing and processing a kind of drug called
"head-rocking pill" in China, the local police department
announced today in Nanning, capital of the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
A total of 25.33 kilograms has been confiscated, together with
7.91 kilograms of compound drugs and a group of drug-producing
instruments, police said.
</P>
<P>
Mo Guanchang, the first suspect, was a salesman for a medicine
manufacturer in Guizhou. Police said the interrogation of Mo led
to the discovery of the key suspects of the case: Yu Hongji and
his niece, Yu Guangqing, both of whom are residents of Macao.
</P>
<P>
The two were arrested in mid-October in Guangzhou, capital of
Guangdong Province. Police also destroyed an underground
drug-processing plant in Guangzhou, confiscating 23,000 pills and
many compound drugs.
</P>
<P>
Yu and his niece told police they had produced more than
250,000 pills since 1996. They brought raw materials into China's
inland areas, then processed them in two medicine manufacturing
plants in Nanning under the guise of producing animal medicine.
</P>
<P>
No information was available on the other two suspects arrested
in the case.
</P>
<P>
The head-rocking pill, so named because it can make abusers
rock their heads constantly, has been identified by doctors as
inflicting severe damage to the abusers' bodies. The drug
reportedly was first used by Westerners, but its consumption has
been on an increase in China's inland areas in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
