<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Urmanov Returns to the Ice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Olympic figure skating
champion Alexei Urmanov has returned to the ice for the first time
since March but failed to quell doubts he will be fit for the
Winter Games in Nagano, according to reports from St Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
Urmanov's exibition performance on Sunday, the final day of the
Cup of Russia competition in St Petersburg, was his first public
appearance since he withdrew from the world championships in
Lausanne with a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
The Rusian national championships, scheduled to be held in
mid-December to choose the Olympic team for next February, will
decide on Urmanov's skating future.
</P>
<P>
Urmanov said he still feels pain from his old injury when he
tries to perform the jumps. "I still can't do the most difficult
jumps," he said.
</P>
<P>
If Urmanov cannot compete in Nagano, two other skaters coached
by Alexei Mishin are ready to step in -- this year's world bronze
medallist Alexei Yagudin, 17, and world junior champion Yevgeny
Plushchenko, who is only 15.
</P>
<P>
Former European champion Ilya Kulik, who trains with coach
Tatyana Tarasova in the United States, is also in the running for
a place in the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
Mishin said: "Urmanov is still my number one skater, although
now I pay the same attention to all three of them."  
</P>
</TEXT>
