<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Reiterates Position on Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today reiterated that
its military operation in northern Iraq is simply aimed at
wiping out the outlawed Kurdish militants there.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly news briefing, Turkish Foreign Ministry
spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that Turkey always respects the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"As we said many times, we don't envisage a permanent
military presence in northern Iraq," Atacanli said, adding that
"Turkish troops will be withdrawn from Iraq as soon as their
objectives are achieved."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly launched cross-border incursions in
northern Iraq to strike the rebels of the Kurdish Workers Party
(PKK) stationed there.
</P>
<P>
In this year's largest operation in May, around 50,000 Turkish
troops entered northern Iraq in a hot pursuit of the PKK rebels,
leading to strong protests from Iran and the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Some units are left in northern Iraq although the Turkish
government announced a withdrawal of troops from the region.
</P>
<P>
As for the continued fighting with the PKK rebels, Atacanli
said that this is the day-to-day operation by the Turkish
military in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry earlier denied the press reports
that Turkey has a plan to build a security zone in northern Iraq in
order to block the infiltration of the PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting for the establishment of an
independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey since 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
