<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Radar Air-Control System for Capital Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's Capital
International Airport next month will introduce a radar air
control system to reduce flight delays.
</P>
<P>
At present, a kind of artificial program control is used to
supervise flights, mainly on the basis of reports from air traffic
controllers. The system has been criticized for its low speed and
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
The existing system can only handle 500 airplanes per day,
accounting for one-tenth that of developed countries, which puts
aircraft too close to each other.
</P>
<P>
The new radar system will provide accurate locations of
aircrafts and easier access to pilots for distance
adjustments. This should greatly increase the aircraft capacity
and ensure flight safety, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Duan Shili, deputy director of the North China Air Control
Bureau of the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC), said
that the effort signals an important transfer in the history of
Chinese civil aviation, and will play an active and far-reaching
role in air transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
