<HEADLINE> Indian Rupee Nose-Dives on Political Uncertainty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Indian rupee nose-dived
to a historic low of 38.50/55 against the U.S. dollar during
trading at the interbank foreign exchange market in Bombay
following frenzied demand for the U.S. unit in the wake of
political uncertainty in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, aggressive dollar selling by the Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) initially in the futures segment and later in the spot
market partly calmed the volatile market, and the rupee attempted
a smart rally.
</P>
<P>
The Indian currency closed at 38.07/13 rupees against the
dollar, an all-time low for a closing quote, steeply lower from
the opening of 37.80/85 and last weekend's finish of 37.75/80.
</P>
<P>
The rupee touched a record low of 38.20/40 rupees for the
dollar in intra-day trade on February 6, 1996. Last Friday, the
local currency dipped to a 21-month low at 37.80, and since then
it has showed a steep downtrend on persistent heavy corporate
dollar purchases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
