<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decline in HK's Tourism Slowing down, Figures Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The latest visitor arrival
statistics released today by the Hong Kong Tourist Association
(HKTA), show a slowdown in the decline in Hong Kong's tourism from
some markets.
</P>
<P>
In October alone, the number of visitors from several markets
including Canada, South and Central America and the Americas as a
region recorded positive growth, although the total number of
arrivals to Hong Kong in the month dropped by 20.7 percent
compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The number of visitors from Canada and South and Central
America increased by 18.0 percent and 61.5 percent respectively
and the Americas as a region showed an increase of two percent.
</P>
<P>
Other markets registering positive growth were France (up 22.3
percent), Italy (up 22.5 percent) New Zealand (up 1.8 percent) and
Singapore (up 3.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from Japan fell by 60.9 percent. The number of
visitors from Taiwan was down by 15.9 percent, while those from
China's interior areas dropped by 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from Europe, Africa and the Middle East were down by
14.6 percent and those from South and Southeast Asia by 19.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
For the period between January and October of this year,
arrivals totaled 8.8 million, a drop of 8.1 percent over the same
period of 1996. But that figure is still about 6.5 percent higher
than the 8.2 million recorded during the same period of 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
