<HEADLINE> Political Crisis in India Deepens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The current political crisis
in India triggered by the release of an investigative report on
the assassination of former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi deepened
today as the ruling United Front refused to punish one of its
constituents allegedly linked to the killing.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Jain Commission report, tabled in the parliament
on November 20, has indicted the Dravida Munnetra Kazagham (DMK),
a major constituent of the United Front, in the assassination of
Rajiv Gandhi in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral a few days
ago, Congress Party President Sitaram Kesri requested the United
Front to remove the three DMK ministers from its government,
saying that the Congress party will otherwise have to withdraw
support for the 17-month-old minority government.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India, Prime Minister Gujral
tonight formally rejected the Congress party's demand.
</P>
<P>
In a letter delivered to Kesri, Gujral said there was no
question of punishing any party or individual in the wake of the
Jain Commission report.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said it was wrong to link the DMK with the
assassination because none of the 41 people so far prosecuted in
the case was ever connected with the regional party in Tamil Nadu.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Congress party earlier today demanded a formal
reply from Gujral to Kesri's letter, saying that the party will
decide its future course of action after receiving a formal
response.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
