<HEADLINE> Province Elects People's Congress Representatives (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Han said, "I will cherish the opportunity as a deputy here. I
will never let you down."
</P>
<P>
The county started the election campaign in September, said
Yang Zaisen, deputy-director of the Standing Committee of Langxi
County People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The county, with a population of 329,000, has more than 233,000
voters. A total of 107 electoral districts are expected to elect
185 deputies.
</P>
<P>
"The right of nomination obviously reflects the democratic
rights of the voters," said Yang.
</P>
<P>
According to China's election law, 10 voters or more can
nominate their own candidate.
</P>
<P>
Up to the beginning of November, the county had 760 nominees,
464 nominated by spontaneous recommending groups of more than nine
electors each. The other 296 were recommended by parties and mass
organizations.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the election margin required by law, 295
formal candidates were chosen after consideration and consultation
between different electoral groups.
</P>
<P>
About 97.6 percent of voters in the county went to the polls,
said electoral staff members. The 185 deputies include 99 workers
and farmers; 63 deputies have no party affiliation; and 46
are women.
</P>
<P>
From the end of this year to the first half of next year,
deputy elections have been under way for people's congresses on
the county level or above, said Liu Zhi, an official of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC) who
supervised the Langxi election.
</P>
<P>
New people's congresses, their standing committees and new
local governments will be elected, she said.
</P>
<P>
The General Office of the NPC Standing Committee issued an
official circular urging local election departments to safeguard
the democratic rights of voters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
