<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Learn Democracy Through Self-Governance (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in more than 60
percent of China's nearly one million villages are now exercising
the right of self-governance. They elect their own village
leadership, monitor its operation and have a say in all major
village affairs.
</P>
<P>
All this started 10 years ago today when the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress, China's legislature, adopted a
Law on the Organization of the Villagers' Committee.
</P>
<P>
The law requires all members of the committee, the formal
village leadership, to be directly elected by the entire village,
thus abolishing the long practice in China's vast countryside that
officials were hand-picked by governments at higher levels.
</P>
<P>
"A fruit of the reform and opening-up drive, this law is a
fundamental one that concerns the interests of all Chinese
farmers," commented Li Baoku, vice-minister of civil affairs.
</P>
<P>
Promulgation and enforcement of the law have helped consolidate
the success of China's rural reforms and brought a positive impact
on the rural society, he added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 25 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities have worked out concrete methods for the
implementation of the law, while most villagers' committees across
the country have undergone three direct elections during the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
"This has laid a wide and solid foundation among the people for
building a socialist democracy in our country, and blazed a trail
for the introduction of socialist democratic politics with Chinese
characteristics in the rural areas," said Li.
</P>
<P>
However, he conceded, the practice of self-governance by
farmers is still in the "primary stage."
</P>
<P>
"To many officials and ordinary people at the grass roots,
villagers' self-governance remains a fresh term," he said. "They
know little about the law, let alone how to implement its articles
one by one."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Steel Giants Merge in Central China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, November 24 (Xinhua) -- China's steel giant, Wuhan Iron
and Steel Complex, today merged with two other large steel firms
which are all in central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan Iron and Steel, together with Daye Iron and Steel Company
and Hubei Iron and Steel Company, are among 300 key companies
supported by the central government and have played an important
role in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan Iron and Steel, a major sheet steel producer, is equipped
with advanced technology and has been one of 57 pilot businesses
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Daye mainly produces special steel while Hubei Iron and Steel
provides markets with quality structural steel.
</P>
<P>
The merger resulted in total capital of 52.1 billion yuan
(about 6.3 billion U.S. dollars), 176,300 employees and a yearly
output of 8 million tons of steel, 7 million tons of iron and 6
million tons of rolled steel.
</P>
<P>
The new iron and steel group will readjust its production
structure and strengthen its competitiveness to become the largest
steel business in central China, said officials from the group.
</P>
<P>
Those brands perviously owned by the three companies will
continue, officials said.
</P>
<P>
General managers from the three companies formed a joint
committee for running the business.  
</P>
</TEXT>
