<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5.2 Million Children Get Free Education in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- A record 5.2 million children
have been registered for free education this year in Uganda, a
country with a population of 20 million, The Monitor reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The number, which is about twice that of last year, has
benefited from the government's Universal Primary Education
(UPE), a free education plan for four children per family,
according to a World Bank statement titled "public information
document".
</P>
<P>
UPE is the government's major effort to improve primary
education which was stagnated during 1970s and earlier 1980s, and
restarted this year.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to assist Uganda in primary education, the World
Bank said International Development Agency (IDA) has proposed a
100-million-dollar education adjustment credit (EAC) scheme to
fund the government in the implementation of UPE. The scheme
will finance 23 percent of budget for primary education, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The IDA money is to be used to hire teachers, provide books
and classrooms for children from poor families to reduce
inequalities in primary and secondary education.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has one of the lowest levels of education in the world
and ranks 158th among the 174 countries in the human development
index of the United Nations Development Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
