<HEADLINE> Chinese, French Chiefs of Staff Hold Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- General Fu Quanyou, chief of
the General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army, held
talks here today with his French counterpart, General
Jean-Philippe Douin.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations have been going well in recent years, Fu
said, and leaders of the two countries have maintained constant
contact.
</P>
<P>
He said political consultations have intensified at all levels
between the two countries. French President Jacques Chirac made a
successful visit to China in May of 1997, said Fu, when the two
countries issued a joint statement indicating they are determined
to establish an all-round partnership oriented toward the 21st
century. This signals that Sino-French ties have entered a new
period of development, he added.
</P>
<P>
With the growth of bilateral relations between the two
countries, the two armed forces have increased their ties, Fu
said, and the Chinese have adopted a positive attitude toward
cooperation between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
As two influential powers in the world, he said both China and
France propose to establish a multi-polar world and bear important
responsibilities for world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a stable cooperative relationship is in
the interests of the people of the two countries, and will be
conducive to a new pattern of Asian-European relations and to a
new international order both politically and economically, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Fu also briefed Douin on Sino-U.S. relations, China's domestic
situation and army-building.
</P>
<P>
Douin agreed with Fu's viewpoints on a multi-polar world and
bilateral relations between the two countries and their armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
He said that France and China share much in common and do not
have any conflicts of interests, and that his country is fully
prepared to engage in high-level strategic dialogue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
