<HEADLINE> Peace Is Pre-requisite for COMESA Development: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba said here today that peace, stability and democratic
governance are essential pre-requisites for the economic growth
and development within the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when officially opening the fourth meeting
of the COMESA council of ministers at Lusaka's Mulungushi
International Conference Center, according to the Zambia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba told the three-day meeting that the major challenge
faced the Lusaka-based regional body is to consolidate efforts in
the creation of an environment which is favorable to political
and economic changes as well as development.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president pointed out that the successful
implementation of COMESA programs such as the creation of a
larger regional market and economic liberalization, will depend
on a peaceful and stable environment.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to attract direct foreign investment to
speed up the industrialization process by making use of the
enormous natural resources in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, he stated that constraints such as uncertain weather
patterns, huge foreign debt and declining prices of raw materials
at the world market have continued to affect negatively the
process of COMESA's economic development, which is aiming to
achieve a free trade zone by 2000 and free movement of capital
and people among its 20 members.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the former union leader also urged individual
member countries to speed up the implementation of collectively
designed programs of COMESA and maintain harmony among regional
economic groupings in the black continent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
