<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Set Up Land Disposal Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Regional government has decided to establish a
committee to monitor the progress of the Land Disposal Program
(LDP) for the coming five years, an official of the HKSAR said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Planning, Environment and Land Bowen Leung said
the Land Disposal Committee will hold its first meeting next
month.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on "Land Bank Policy" organized by the
Hong Kong Project Management Exchange Center Limited, Leung said
the LDP would roll forward each year and the committee would also
work out the second five-year LDP with details expected to be
announced in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase land supply and build up land reserve, the
government has committed to developing 10 strategic growth areas,
which are estimated to provide sufficient land for 270,000 housing
units capable of accommodating 720,000 people between 2006 and
2011, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that due to the scarcity of land resources, the
government needs to carry out reclamation projects, as
appropriate, and set up land reserve so as to cope with future
development and meet public demand for housing.
</P>
<P>
The government will provide enough land for housing through the
 five-year LDP. Together with the residential redevelopment
projects carried out by both the public and private sectors, the
government is confident that the target will be achieved to
provide at least 85,000 housing units a year effective from 1999,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Leung noted that despite the fact that the property market has
softened during the past few weeks, the government's commitment to
 provide sufficient land to meet housing demand would not be
affected. The government would continue to dispose of land
according to the LDP, he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
