<HEADLINE> Over 2 Million Tanzanians to Have AIDS by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The National AIDS
Control Program (NACP) has warned that some 2.4 million
Tanzanians will be infected with AIDS by the year 2000 if no
strenuous efforts are made to fight against the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
The warning was given in Dar es Salaam over the weekend by the
Acting NACP Program Manager, Dr Mwita Nyang'anyi, when closing a
two-week AIDS Care and Management Facilitation course, The
Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
He told the 15 course participants from various parts of the
east African country that care for AIDS patients would be given
priority by the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, which has a population of 30 million, currently has
1.5 million AIDS patients or carriers.
</P>
<P>
"This care must guarantee confidentiality and avoid
discrimination, and allow a patient to live a normal life as much
as possible," Dr Nyang'anyi said.
</P>
<P>
He calls on people to make effort in carrying out the policy
on sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) issued in 1995, which
covers the key areas of institutional care and management of
STDs, community-based support services, protection of care
workers and orphans.
</P>
<P>
Dr Nyang'anyi expressed hope that the training activities
which include theory and basic skills would be valuable for
reducing AIDS cases by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
