<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troubled Yamaichi Voluntarily Closes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Yamaichi Securities Co., one of
Japan's big four brokerages, will end its century-long business
due to its financial crisis, Japanese Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka announced today.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi filed with the Finance Ministry earlier in the day for
voluntary closure to terminate operations in the face of a
short-term liquidity crunch and a weakening capital base.
</P>
<P>
The demise of the Tokyo-based Yamaichi is projected to leave
behind an estimated 3 trillion yen (about 23.9 billion dollars) in
unresolved debts, making it the largest Japanese business failure
in history.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuzuka told an emergency press conference that Yamaichi
clients' assets will be protected with the use of the Bank of
Japan's special unsecured loans.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Japanese monetary authorities will do their
utmost in cooperation with foreign counterparts so that Yamaichi's
woes do not cause a crisis.
</P>
<P>
Market confidence in Yamaichi declined on persistent rumors
that the firm is engaged in improper "tobashi" deals in which
brokerages temporarily shift investment losses from one client to
another to help a favored customer avoid reporting losses.
</P>
<P>
The brokerage's image was also tarnished by the payoff scandal
earlier this year involving a "sokaiya" corporate racketeer.
</P>
<P>
The failures of two other financial institutions this month
prompted a further plunge in stock prices, making it extremely
difficult for the already cash-strapped Yamaichi to raise funds to
meet day-to-day needs.
</P>
<P>
Sanyo Securities Co., a second-tier brokerage, went bust
November 3. It was followed by the bankruptcy on November 17 of
Hokkaido Takushoku Bank, one of Japan's top 10 nationwide
full-service commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi held an extraordinary board meeting this morning to
formalize a plan to end its century-long history.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know how to apologize to investors and clients who
have patronized us for many years," Yamaichi President Shohei
Nozawa told a press conference at the Tokyo Stock Exchange,
announcing the company's decision to dissolve itself.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the collapse of Yamaichi, Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto pledged to take all necessary steps to maintain
stability in the financial system and protect investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
