<HEADLINE> RCCK Founding Anniversary Marked in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ninth National Congress of
the Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang (RCCK) and
concurrently the meeting to mark the 50th anniversary of its
founding opened here today.
</P>
<P>
This is the last congress of the RCCK in this century. The RCCk
was founded in 1948 in Hong Kong by the patriotic democrats in the
Kuomintang and other patriotic democrats, and now it has more than
53,000 members.
</P>
<P>
Chinese State President and General Secretary of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Jiang Zemin wrote
an inscription to mark the RCCK's 50th anniversary, which read
"upholding socialist and patriotic banner and dedicating to the
rejuvenation of the Chinese nation and the reunification of the
motherland."
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng, Chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress Qiao Shi and Chairman of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) Li Ruihuan also wrote their inscriptions for
the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the occasion on behalf of the CPC Central Committee
in a message of congratulations, Wu Bangguo, vice-premier and
member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee, said
that "it is the common aspiration of all the Chinese people to
achieve the reunification of their motherland."
</P>
<P>
He said that it was stressed once again at the 15th National
Congress of the CPC to adhere to the basic principle of "peaceful
reunification, and one country, two systems" in promoting the
relations across the Taiwan Straits and the process of the
peaceful reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
He said that since it enjoyed close contacts with the people
of various sector in Hong Kong, Taiwan and Macao as well as in
other parts of the world, the RCCK is playing a special role in
the peaceful reunification of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the CPC Central Committee hopes that the RCCK will
promote its function to promote the economic, scientific and
cultural exchanges across the Taiwan Straits and to help achieve
the reunification of the motherland in line with Jiang Zemin's
eight-point proposal on the question of the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
He Luli, executive chairwoman of the Congress, urged the RCCK
to uphold and carry forward Sun Yat-sen's patriotic, revolutionary
and progressive spirit to dedicate to the reunification of the
country and make an active response to Jiang Zemin's proposal.
</P>
<P>
Ding Shisun, chairman of the Central Committee of the China
Democratic League, read out a message of congratulations on behalf
of other non-communist parties and the All-China Federation of
Industry and Commerce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
