<HEADLINE> S'pore To Increase Spending for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will spend five
percent of its Gross Domestic Product (GDP) on education, one
percentage point more than presently in efforts to upgrade the
country's educational system, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien
Loong said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of a forum on Singapore's education, Lee
said: "We are presently spending four percent of GDP on education.
We need to raise this to five percent of GDP."
</P>
<P>
"These are long term investments which we should make in good
times and in bad, so long as we can afford them, unlike other
items of more discretionary spending," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that by focusing on education, Singapore will
maintain and improve its lead over competitors, and this will give
Singapore a long term advantage which will not be easily lost.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will focus its resources on the three
areas of teachers, infrastructure and technology.
</P>
<P>
He said there are plans to recruit 2,000 teachers "of the right
quality" steadily over the next decade to improve the
teacher-pupil ratios.
</P>
<P>
There are also plans to upgrade schools and junior colleges in
the country. Every school will have computer laboratories, larger
classrooms, pastoral care and counseling rooms and offices, and
infrastructure like power systems and computer networks are also
needed to support the new activities, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
