<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV to Infect 1 Million Children by End of 1997: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) today stressed the need to educate young people about AIDS
and urged countries to take stronger measures in the face of a
growing number of kids infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued today, the Manila-based WHO regional
office for the western Pacific said that about 400,000 children
under the age of 15 were infected with the human immunodeficiency
virus (HIV), the virus that causes AIDS, worldwide in 1996 alone,
bringing the total number of kids infected with the virus in this
age group to 830,000.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, 1 million children in this age group will
be infected with HIV and more than 90 percent of them will be in
developing countries, said the press release issued in connection
with the observance of this year's World AIDS Day on December 1.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the epidemic, the press release said, some 3
million children below 15 years old have developed AIDS and most
of them have died.
</P>
<P>
Also by the year 2000, WHO estimated, there will be more than
1.8 million HIV cases in the West Pacific region, including
children and adolescents. There are currently more than 700,000
people in the region infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
"The HIV proceeds more rapidly to AIDS in children than in
adults," WHO regional office director S. T. Han said, stressing
that mother to child transmission, blood transfusion and sexual
contact are the major transmission routes of AIDS to kids.
</P>
<P>
"Education, both in and out of schools, is one of the most
effective ways of restricting the spread of HIV," Han added.
</P>
<P>
He urged countries and areas to unite and take urgent measures
to give children around the world hope for the future in a world
with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Children, young people and their families need support in their
everyday life so that their risk of exposure to HIV can be
minimized, he said, adding that "the responsibility lies with the
governments, health professionals, communities and families."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book Published on Impact of European Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China and
Credit Suisse First Boston today announced the official launch of
a book on the European Union: "The Euro: Reshaping Europe's
Financial Markets."
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Zhenming, deputy managing director of the
International Department of the People's Bank of China, the start
of the European Monetary Union and the Euro is set for Jan. 1,
1999. With the introduction of a single currency, the European
Union's financial system will undergo significant change.
</P>
<P>
The book is designed to provide insight into the anticipated
impact of the single currency on the European financial
markets. The book reviews the changes in financial sources and
analyzes the future of government bonds, as well as its impact on
the futures, stock and foreign exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese official said that the book has been conceived in
view of the rapid development of China's financial markets as well
as the growing involvement of Chinese entities in international
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
The joint publication of "The Euro" reflects the common
interest of the People's Bank of China and the Credit Suisse First
Boston with regard to European financial markets, the official
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
