<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Asset Evaluation Industry Growing Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Asset evaluation is playing an
increasingly important role in optimizing the distribution of
resources and facilitating economic restructuring in China, a
senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
The business, which used to cover the state-owned sector only,
now involves the private sector. It is also expected to cover a
greater variety of economic activities such as real estate
management, taxation and mortgage guarantees, said Pan Yue, deputy
director-general of the State Administration of State Property.
</P>
<P>
Chinese asset-evaluation agencies conducted more than 50,900
evaluations in 1996, with the net book value of the assets
evaluated at 717.8 billion yuan and the appraised value at more
than one trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The evaluations resulted in a net increase of 291.2 billion
yuan in asset value, which translates into an asset value
appreciation rate of 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, the appraised asset value last year was
282.5 billion yuan, or 39 percent more than that of 1995. In the
first 10 months of this year, Chinese evaluation agencies
appraised more than 200 billion yuan worth of property for
enterprises to be listed on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that currently China has more than 3,300
asset evaluation agencies and more than 55,000 asset appraisers,
including 5,800 certified public asset evaluators.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West African Countries Plan Common Law on Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Central bank officials from
five west African countries, namely, Nigeria, Sierra Leone,
Ghana, Liberia and the Gambia are expected to meet in Abuja next
week to adopt a common law on money laundering, the Guardian
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The law will provide for the establishment of an anti-money
laundering agency in each country, with representatives from the
central bank, the police, the corporate affair commission, the
drug law enforcement agency, immigration and the justice
ministry, among others, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The agency will have the power to place any bank account under
surveillance, tap any telephone line, probe into any business
activities, stop any suspected transactions and prosecute
offenders at a special court.
</P>
<P>
The law will make it mandatory for casinos to keep records of
gamblers and their transactions for at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
It also requires financial institutions such as banks and
exchange services to report all transactions in excess of one
million Naira (about 12,500 U.S. dollars) by an individual or
five million Naira (about 62,500 dollars) in the case of a
company.
</P>
<P>
Of the five countries, only Nigeria now has a special law on
money laundering. The lack of such law has been described by
experts as a major cause of distress in African banking systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
