<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Set up Standard Asset Valuation System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- China will strive to establish
a highly scientific and standard asset valuation system in 10 to
15 years, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"We want to make asset appraising an intermediate service
industry that plays by the rule of independence, objectivity and
fairness and meets the need of the development of a socialist
market economy," Pan Yue, deputy director-general of the State
Administration of State Property said at a meeting on asset
valuation.
</P>
<P>
To that end, China will set up for asset valuation a unified
legal system, a unified self-discipline management system, a
unified set of appraising methods and standards, a unified
research, education and training system, and a unified information
networking system, Pan said.
</P>
<P>
To meet the requirements on the development of the
intermediate service industry set forth by the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China in September, the asset
valuation industry must achieve several major shifts, such as the
shift from mainly safeguarding the rights and interests of the
owners of state assets to safeguarding the rights and interests of
all economic entities, the deputy director-general said.
</P>
<P>
Asset valuation management will shift from government-oriented
management to professional self-discipline while management
will focus not only on asset valuation agencies and projects but
also on certified asset valuers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
