<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Administration Over House Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Administrative Rules
for Urban House Property Right Registration will be put into
effect as of Jan. 1, 1998, Li Zhendong, vice-minister of
construction, said here today.
</P>
<P>
By then, homeowners in all large cities will have to use a
unified house property right certificate issued by the Ministry of
Construction. In other cities such a certificate will be available
to the homeowners no later than July 1.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference, Li said it is a common practice
worldwide to register house property rights while in China
homeowners are issued ownership certificates.
</P>
<P>
China started the registration process in 1987, the official
said, and now 80 percent of the country's urban houses have been
registered.
</P>
<P>
Li said it is important to protect the rights and interests of
homeowners by setting up a registration system of house property
rights.
</P>
<P>
As early as 1987, China issued a provisional rule on
registering urban house property rights, which has become
incompatible with the existing situation, Li said, because of
people's increased legal consciousness and fresh economic
development.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the current rules were worked out on the
basis of the country's Administrative Law over Urban Real Estate
as well as other laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The current rules are more complete in content, Li said, with
detailed articles concerning the registration organs, scope and
legal responsibilities of those who violate the rules.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
