<HEADLINE> US U-2 Surveillance Plane Flys Over Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said that a U-2 spy plane
of the United States entered its airspace this morning, the Iraqi
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The plane intruded Iraq's airspace at 9:30 local time (0530
GMT) over the southern city of Basra, and then flew over the Kafri
District along the Iraqi-Iranian border, an Iraqi Foreign Ministry
spokesman told the agency.
</P>
<P>
The U-2 avoided the Iraqi air defense force, and Iraqi military
leaders were tracking its flights very closely, he said.
</P>
<P>
U-2's surveillance flight is part of the inspection mission of
the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) which oversees the
dismantling of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had accused the plane of serving U.S. intelligence
services and threatened to shoot it down, which together with
Iraq's expulsion of the American arms experts had triggered a
three-week standoff.
</P>
<P>
The crisis ended after intensified Russian diplomatic efforts
and the inspectors of UNSCOM, including the Americans, were
allowed to return to Baghdad to continue their work.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that the U.S. had wished to make other
peoples kneel down by brutal force, which he said is an illusion
to be smashed in the Middle East, particularly in the Arab world.
</P>
