<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bohai Sea Zone Expected to be China's Third Economic Engine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bohai Sea Zone is expected
to become China's third economic engine following the Pearl River
and Yangtze River deltas, according to local economists.
</P>
<P>
Young economists, officials and industrialists started a
two-day seminar here today to discuss development strategy in the
region to enhance mutual understanding and put forward concrete
measures to speed up regional economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was jointly organized by youth federations in
Beijing, Tianjin, Hebei, Shandong and Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai Sea Zone includes the Liaodong Penninsula, the
Beijing-Tianjin-Tangshan belt, the coastal belt of Hebei Province,
the Yellow River delta and the Jiaodong Peninsula. The region is
one of China's key political and cultural centers, and one of the
major blocs in its economic development agenda.
</P>
<P>
The zone boasts rich mineral resources, sound agricultural and
industrial bases, and well-developed transportion and
telecommunications networks to fuel future sustained growth. In
the next five years, Beijing and Tianjin alone plan to invest 500
billion yuan in infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Geographically, the region is in the vicinity of Russia,
Mongolia, the Korean Penninsula and Japan. Also, key port cities
such as Lianyungang, Dalian and Tianjin are eastern starting
points of the EurAsia Continental Bridge linking China with Middle
Asia, the Middle East and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The keynote report at the seminar indicated that East Asia has
become one of the fastest-growing regions in the world and a hot
spot for international capital. Conditions combined to create a
favorable environment for development of the Bohai Sea Zone.
</P>
<P>
The report suggested setting up a regional economic community
with the eventual target of building an economic center in
northern China and a high-tech product export base.
</P>
<P>
Also, the report suggested innovation in traditional industries
in the region and fostering such industries as automotive,
electronics, machinery, metallurgical, chemical and service for
future economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Experts urged more institutional reform, particularly in
enterprise-ownership reform, to combat the adverse effect of
scattered capital input and unclear policies from different local
governments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
