<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Greek Defense Ministers Confer in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian said here today that to develop friendly cooperative
relations between the two countries and two armed forces of China
and Greece is not only in the fundamental interests of the two
peoples but also serves world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also vice-chairman of China's Central Military Commission
and state councillor, made the remarks during talks with Greek
counterpart Akis Tsohatzopoulos, who arrived here at Chi's
invitation.
</P>
<P>
Extending the welcome to Tsohatzopoulos' on his first China
visit, Chi said that the two countries, both nations with ancient
civilization, have seen smooth development in bilateral relations,
adding that the two countries share the identical or similar views
on the major international issues.
</P>
<P>
China is a developing socialist country, the nature of the
social system and its national development strategy decide its
defense-oriented policy, Chi said, adding that China never seeks
hegemonism and forges military alliances with other countries.
</P>
<P>
China will reduce its armed forces by half a million people
during the next three years, following a reduction of one million in
the 1980s, Chi said. This not only is conducive to bettering troops
with Chinese characteristics, he said, but also benefits
maintaining world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos said that China, as a permanent member of the
Security Council of the United Nations, plays an important role in
international affairs. He expressed hope of enhancing cooperation
with China in the economy, national security and the defense
industry.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos also exchanged views with Chi on the
international security situation and other issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
Kui Fulin, deputy chief of the general staff of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army was among those present at the talks.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Chi presided over a welcome ceremony in
honor of Tsohatzopoulos and accompanied him in an honor-guard
review. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
