<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Urges Bangladesh to Speed up Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- World Bank (WB) President James
D. Wolfensohn has suggested that Bangladesh speed up reforms in
the sectors of finance, education, water resources management and
government administration.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn made the suggestion in a letter to Bangladeshi Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina about his recent visit to the country. The
letter was delivered by the World Bank's office in Dhaka on
November 9, the Independent newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reforms in the above-mentioned four areas should be given
particular attention in order to accelerate the development of the
country, Wolfensohn stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the government's efforts, weak management
of nationalized banks, a worsening loan default situation and lack
of efforts to improve the governance of banks were impeding
financial discipline.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for firmness on the part of the prime
minister to lead the reform activities.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said the World Bank's office in Bangladesh had been
asked to assist the government in developing a 10-year vision for
the education sector.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank chief said he had suggested immediate
implementation of a plan to rationalize the government structure.
Progress in implementing his suggestion would be reviewed after
four months and a decision would be made on what additional steps
could be taken for further development, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, several projects funded by and the IDA
(International Development Association) would also be reviewed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Copies of the letter were also sent to ministers of education,
health and family welfare, water resources, and the Public
Administration Reform Commission, and the governor of the
Bangladesh Bank, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
