<HEADLINE> McRae Crashes to Dent His Title Hope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Briton Colin McRae's hope to
win his world title was dented after going off the road in thick
fog on the opening stage of Monday's second leg in the British RAC
auto rally held at Cheltenham.
</P>
<P>
McRae lost more than one minute in the incident on the
18.65-kilometer stage at Radnor and dropped to eighth overall.
</P>
<P>
He wins the world title event only if he takes the top honor at
RAC here and Finland rival Tommi Makinen finishes outside the top
six,
</P>
<P>
McRae's mishap was welcome news for Makinen, who moved up to
fourth at the end of the stage after overnight third-placed driver
Didier Auriol dropped to 10th when he ran too cautiously through
the fog-hit stage.
</P>
<P>
Makinen needs to finish in the top six in the RAC Rally to lift
his second consecutive world championship crown.
</P>
<P>
Briton Richard Burns, Makinen's teammate at Mitsubishi, was
fastest overall on the stage and opened a 25-second lead over
Spain's Carlos Sainz.
</P>
<P>
The day's remaining six stages will take the teams around
central Wales before a return to the Cheltenham base on Monday
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
