<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD Meets on Competition Laws, Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Conference
on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) today started a three-day expert
meeting on the application of competition laws and policies.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting here, participants will exchange views and
experiences on three major issues related to the application of
competition laws and policies:
</P>
<P>
- The treatment of restrictive practices such as selective
distribution, exclusive dealing and franchising;
</P>
<P>
- Ways and means of promoting a "competition culture;"
</P>
<P>
- International aspects of competition and the problems for
competition law enforcement, including international mergers and
industrial concentration which affect other countries; and the
strengthening of international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The participants will also consider a study prepared by the
UNCTAD Secretariat on the empirical evidence of the benefits
derived from applying the principles of competition law and policy
to economic development, so as to attain greater efficiency in
international trade and development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the only international forum where all
countries, developed and developing, as well as those in
transition, meet to discuss specific competition policy issues,
UNCTAD says in its press release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
