<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Share prices rose sharply in
moderate trading on the Singapore market today as the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials Index surged by 39.45 points to close at
1,681.85 points today.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said that the market benefited from investors who fled
from markets elsewhere in the region and bought Singapore blue
chips instead. However, the overall mood was still cautious as the
market braced for the reaction to the collapse of Yamaichi in the
Japanese market, which was closed today for a holiday and will
open tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume stood at 180.55 million units, worth
348.78 million Singapore dollars (about 219.36 million US
dollars). Advances and declines were equal at 170 counters each,
while 276 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded counter as
it registered a turnover of 25.5 million units. It was followed by
Innovest Bhd which had 9.55 million shares traded. Renong Bhd was
next with 8.97 million of its shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 1.3 dollars to finish at 22.4 Singapore
dollars. Creative 50 and the Singapore Airlines (SIA) Foreign
increased by 50 cents each to end at 46 and 11 Singapore dollars
respectively. City Development picked up by 45 cents to close at
8.2 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Berland was the biggest loser as it declined
by 31 cents to end at 0.42 dollar. Uniphoenix fell by 28 cents to
close at 4.02 Singapore dollars, while GE Life lost 20 cents to
finish at 11.6 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
