<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Lifts Freeze on Foreign Labor in Plantation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
has agreed to lift a freeze on the intake of foreign labor in the
plantation industry which is focusing on export-oriented
activities to boost production.
</P>
<P>
However, such a move will be temporary until the government
finds out a long-term solution to the problem of labor shortage in
the plantation industry, Primary Industries Minister Lim Keng Yaik
told reporters here today after officiating the Fourth Malaysian
Palm Oil Promotion Council Annual Seminar.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia imposed a freeze on foreign labor in the plantation
industry at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, Lim said, Malaysia's plantation industry needs
some 50,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
He added that the shortage of labor, which is one of the major
constraints for the plantation industry, has caused and will
continue to cause losses of about 1.08 billion ringgit (about 310
million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
According to Lim, by 1996, Malaysia had planted 2.62 million
hectares of land with oil palm trees and the area under such trees
is projected to increase to about 2.9 million hectares by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Bullish crude palm oil prices have been quoted on the Kuala
Lumpur Commodities Exchange recently. The prices of palm oil now
hover above the level of 1,700 ringgit (about 488.5 dollars) per
ton, from 1,100 ringgit (about 316 dollars) per ton in the middle
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, India and China are Malaysia's leading palm oil
export markets.
</P>
<P>
Lim said palm oil prices have gone up due to currency
fluctuation, a recent haze and the El-Nino phenomenon as well as
the effects of labor shortage on production.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would implement a price stabilizing
mechanism to prevent unnecessary increases in the price of
domestic cooking oil and his ministry is currently working on the
establishment of the mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Lim criticized a report which suggested that palm oil-based
cooking oil be replaced by coconut oil, saying the report could
ruin the efforts made to promote the palm oil industry in the
domestic and international markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
