<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Unchanged in Light Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
remained largely unchanged in light trade today as investors were
cautious of Asia's direction and the possible impact of the
collapse of the Japanese stockbroker Yamaichi Securities.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed down 0.6 points to 2482.1, with
a marginal improvement in industrials offset by a slight fall in
resource stocks.
</P>
<P>
"Generally the market remained steady. The reduction in
turnover came because of Tokyo being closed today which gave the
market a lack of direction given that markets are still a bit
uncertain because of the Asian problems," Jamie Spiteri from Shaw
Stockbroking said.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a light 268.44 million shares at a value
of 467.47 million U.S. dollars, with falls outnumbering rises by
588 to 475.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index closed 2.8 points higher at 4226.8.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts fell 4 cents to 2.67 Australian
dollars on a turnover of 41 million shares while News Corp.
ordinary shares rose 13 cents to 7.52 Australian dollars and
preferred shares 7.7 cents to 6.89 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank was the best performer among banking stocks
today, improving 21.5 cents to 17.47 Australian dollars after
starting its buyback scheme on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Westpac shares also rose, closing 5 cents higher at 9.12
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank fell 14 cents to 19.81 Australian
dollars and ANZ 13.6 cents to 10.05 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index shed 3.7 points to 1093.4, with the
major stocks split between rises and falls.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP shares slid 15 cents, after rising on
Friday, with a fire at its Port Kembla steel plant and falling
copper prices among the affecting factors. BHP closed at 13.65
Australian dollars with a turnover of 4 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto shares jumped 38.2 cents to 16.577
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks generally rose as the bullion price increased 1.25
U.S. dollars per ounce to 304.75 U.S. dollars. The gold index
added nine points to reach 946.6.  
</P>
</TEXT>
