<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Lu Qin Retains World Xiangqi Championships Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Two-time world champion Lu
Qin from China retained his men's individual title with a
top-ranked point total at the Fifth World Xiangqi (Chinese Chess)
Championships which closed here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lu, a 35-year-old Grand Master from South China's Guangdong
Province, completed the nine-round competitions unbeaten and
accumulated a total of 17 points from eight wins and a tie.
</P>
<P>
Lu began to learn the game at the age of eight and won the
national junior champion title at 16. With victories both at
domestic and international competitions, he is now the top-ranked
player in China.
</P>
<P>
Ranked second and third in the men's individual event were
another Grand Master from Guangdong Province, Xu Yinchuan, 22, and
Chinese Taipei's veteran player and Grand Master Wu Kui Lin, 35.
</P>
<P>
In the women's individual event, it was a former Chinese
national champion, Lin Ye, who won the top honor with a total of
14 points from six wins and two draws. Lin, who is native in
Chengdu of Southwest China's Sichuan Province, immigrated to Italy
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Gao Yiping, 21, from East China's Jiangsu Province,
took the second place with 13 points from six wins, one tie and
one loss, and another former Chinese player, Guo Shu Long took the
third place.
</P>
<P>
China also won the men's team title.
</P>
<P>
And the non-Chinese event's top honor was taken by
Mai-Thanh-Minh from Vietnam and Frenchman Dang Thanh Trung won the
second place.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision made at an earlier conference here of
the World Xiangxi Federation, the game's world governing body, the
next two world championships are scheduled for 1999 in Macao and
2001 in Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
