<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Human Resources Held in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of human resources
practitioners, consultants and academics are gathered here to
explore the challenges and opportunities of the profession in the
years ahead.
</P>
<P>
A two-day annual conference of the Hong Kong Institute of Human
 Resources Management (IHRM) opened today. Some 40 speakers, who
are mostly human resources professionals and business executives,
are expected to address the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The role and function of human resources, competencies that
human resources practitioners will need to acquire, the evolving
role of training for human resources development, and the impact
of information technology will be among the key issues to be
discussed at the gathering.
</P>
<P>
"In recognition of the important year of 1997, Moving Beyond
1997 is selected as the theme for the conference," said IHRM
President Eddie Ng, who noted that the profession will definitely
undergo revolutionary, not evolutionary, changes in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
The conference consists of five plenary sessions and 20
concurrent seminars. Issues on people management in China's inland
areas and the Asia-Pacific region, including the topic on
compensation and benefits, are to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
Findings of the research project "Human resources management
strategies and practices in foreign invested enterprises in the
People's Republic of China" were released at the conference. The
project is a joint research by the IHRM, Hong Kong's leading human
resources professional body, and the Institute of International
Technology and Economy under the Development Research Center of
the State Council of the PRC, conducted since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying the conference is an exhibition featuring
leading-edge services and products provided by professional
consultants and vendors. One of the exhibitors, the South China
Market of Human Resources, shows their on-line job-matching system
covering several major cities in China's inland areas. A book
store is also set up to display related publications.
</P>
<P>
IHRM, founded in 1977 with the aim of safeguarding the interest
of the human resources profession and enhance its influence at
various levels, now has more than 2,800 members among which 250
are corporate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
