<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Start Air Route to Nanjing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Macao is to start a regular air
service to Nanjing, capital of East China's Jiangsu Province, next
April while a chartered flight service will be inaugurated next
month, the Macao Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Yang Qilong, deputy general manager of the China Travel
Service (Jiangsu) Group Company, who signed a chartered flight
service agreement with Air Macao last weekend, said the new air
route is aimed at attracting more Taiwan passengers.
</P>
<P>
The air service has great potential as Nanjing has a large
number of Taiwan investors, Yang noted.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the quasi-direct flight service between Taiwan and
Beijing, Shanghai and Xiamen via Macao has attracted many Taiwan
passengers. Experts estimated that about 70 percent of the
passengers of Air Macao are from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The first chartered flight will start on December 29,
according to the agreement. There will be two round flights each
week and the air travel will take two hours and 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Li Keli, general manager of Air Macao, told the Macao Daily
News that the regular flight service is expected to begin next
April upon approval by aviation authorities in China's mainland
and Macao.
</P>
<P>
By then, Air Macao will have 11 regular air routes, six of
which to China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the airline plans to start regular service to
Chongqing City in Southwest China later next year and prepares for
the start of air routes to Guilin in Southeast China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region and Hangzhou in East China's Zhejiang
Province and to Malaysia, Singapore and Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Hotel Room Occupancy Rate Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The average hotel room occupancy
rate in Macao during the first nine months of this year dropped by
10.8 percent compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
show that a total of 1,670,956 passengers checked in Macao hotels
during the January-September period, down 16.8 percent from the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the number of passengers who stayed in hotels of
four stars and above plunged by 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of passengers in tourist groups also dropped during
the period.
</P>
<P>
Only 774,183 passengers arrived in groups in the first nine
months of this year, down 14.5 percent. Most came from China's
inland, Taiwan, Japan and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In September, Macao had 8,324 hotel rooms available for
passengers, up 8.3 percent from a year earlier. The per-capita
time a checked-in passenger stayed in Macao was 1.34 nights, up
0.11 nights from September last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
