<HEADLINE> UN Arms Inspectors Continue Mission in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations weapons
inspection teams continued their mission today for the third
consecutive day after they returned to Baghdad on Friday, the
Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi official who did not give his name said that eight
teams left here between 8 and 9 a.m. local time (0500-0600 GMT)
for a number of sites marked for U.N. permanent inspection.
</P>
<P>
The maintenance team of the monitoring cameras would inspect 16
sites to make sure that the cameras installed there were in proper
operation while the helicopter team would make two flights over
some Iraqi military bases, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the agency quoted an anonymous U.N. inspector as
saying that the experts did not anticipate any difficulties or
obstacles that might be caused by the Iraqis in their work.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. inspectors carried out their mission smoothly and
without interference in the previous two days.
</P>
<P>
Iraq allowed the 75 U.N. inspectors, including four Americans,
to be back on Friday after a three-week standoff that erupted
after Iraq accused the Americans of being spies and threw them out.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors working for the U.N. Special Commission are
trying to verify that Iraq has complied with the U.N. orders
issued in 1991 at the end of the Gulf War to destroy its weapons
of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Only then will the U.N. Security Council lift the crippling
economic sanctions imposed on Iraq in August 1990 when its troops
invaded Kuwait, touching off the Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
