<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Lionel Jospin Sunday took advantage of the
assistance from his partisans at the Socialist Party congress to
retaliate against the criticism by President Jacques Chirac over his
employment policy. Chirac has warned Jospin against ``hazardous
experimentations'' in his job policy. Jospin joked that what was
really ``hazardous'' was for Chirac to dissolve the parliament and
hold early general elections this spring.
</P>
<P>
-- One week after the massacre of Luxor, it is time to settle
account. After sacking his interior minister, Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak turned to abroad to seek scape-goats by violently
attacking European countries for providing refuge to Islamists and
indirectly holding them responsible for the massacre.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In his closing speech at the Socialist Party congress on
Sunday in Brest, Lionel Jospin responded, and for the first time
without caution, to the criticism of the chief of state, creating a
net tension in the cohabitation. ``I remember a hazardous
experimentation which began on April 21, 1997... in the electoral
matter in connection with the dissolution (of parliament),'' said
Jospin ironically in front of the Socialist militants, in response
to a warning given by Chirac against ``the mirage of hazardous
experimentations'' by his government.
</P>
<P>
-- Asked in a poll by Le Figaro and some other press institutions
on the political situation of the Provcene-Alpes-Cote d'Azur region
in southern France, 79 percent of the local inhabitants said that
corruption exists in their region, while 59 percent said that
corruption is ``neither more nor less serious'' in the region than
other regions of France. Sixty percent said that there exist
``mafia behaviors'' in the local political circles, and 86 percent
said that this corruption is the expression of a more general
degradation of the political life in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
