<HEADLINE> Iran's Basij Force Vows to Defend Supreme Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Basij (volunteer
mobilization) force commander, Ali Reza Afshar, today vowed to
defend the country's Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the Basij headquarters here
on the occasion of the 18th anniversary of its formation, Afshar
said his force would fight against any plots against the supreme
leadership, Velayat-e Faqih (governance of supreme religious
jurisprudent).
</P>
<P>
He praised recent political demonstrations to support the
supreme leader but denied there were any attacks on a prominent
religious figure, Ayatollah Hussein Ali Montazeri, who formerly
had been designated as successor to the late Supreme Leader
Ayatollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that hundreds of
religious instructors and students Wednesday attacked Montazeri's
office in the religious city of Qom, some 100 kilometers south of
the capital, following his criticism of Khamenei's interference in
government affairs.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Iranian Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance
Ataollah Mohajerani also termed Velayat-e Faqih, national unity
and territorial integrity as three principles of the duty of the
Basij.
</P>
<P>
Afshar said the Basij force would hold a ceremony Wednesday to
reiterate its allegiance to Ayatollah Khamenei, who is also the
commander-in-chief of the country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the Basij would hold a nationwide
maneuver on Wednesday to strengthen its buildup and defensive
capability, with the participation of some 5 million volunteers
from all strata.
</P>
<P>
Terming defending the country and assistance to the people as
the two main duties of the Basij, he said his force has
contributed much to the country's defensive, security, relief and
constructive programs during the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
The Basij commander noted that so far there were 5 million
Basij soldiers under his command, hoping the figure would rise to
20 million in the near future, an ideal set by Iran's late
Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
Afshar noted that his force was divided in three parts named as
regular, active and special, adding that the Basij force would be
turned into a part of the country's Islamic Revolution Guards
Corps (IRGC) at a time of defending the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
