<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu to Propose Further Redeployments: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu is preparing a new proposal on further troop
redeployments in the West Bank, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is considering pulling out troops from 6-8 percent
of the areas under Israeli control in the second phase of the
three-stage pullbacks as stipulated in the Hebron agreement
signed last January, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu conditioned the first and second phases of troop
pullbacks on a promise by the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) to continue combating terror and its agreement to
immediately hold the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also proposed completing the final phase of pullbacks
as a part of the final settlement.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu held consultations Sunday on the further
redeployments with senior Cabinet ministers, including Foreign
Minister David Levy, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, and
Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Under the Hebron agreement, Israel should have completed the
first stage pullback by March 7 this year, and the second stage by
September 7.
</P>
<P>
In early March, Israel approved the scope of the first stage
redeployment as only 9 percent, which was rejected by the
Palestinian side which demanded for at least 30 percent. Due to
the failure to carry out the first stage pullback, the second
stage has also been delayed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's move to consider further redeployments came amid
mounting pressure from both the Palestinian side and the United
States, which is becoming increasingly impatient with the current
stalemate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a public speech last Friday, U.S. President Bill Clinton
publicly expressed his dissatisfaction with the current state of
the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, warning that the window of
opportunity is narrowing with the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
As a sign pointing to Clinton's anger toward Netanyahu's
policy of intransigency, the U.S. president refused to meet
Netanyahu during the latter's recent visit to the U.S. to attend a
conference of Jewish federations.
</P>
<P>
Anticipating the government's move to carry out further troop
pullbacks, hardline Jewish settlers and rightist lawmakers
threatened to topple the government if it hands over more land to
the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Michael Kleiner, a rightist lawmaker and head of the powerful
Land of Israel Front in the Knesset (Parliament), warned Netanyahu
Sunday against agreeing to a freeze of settlement construction and
transferring more land to the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Kleiner said his group, which comprises 18 lawmakers within
the ruling coalition, would vote against the government on future
issues, a move that will bring down the government.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli law requires the government to secure 61 votes in
the 120-seat Knesset. If it fails, the government will step down
to pave the way for holding new elections both for the prime
minister and the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu government is now holding a 66-seat majority in
the Knesset, but it cannot survive even six coalition lawmakers
defect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Halts Diesel Trade With Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has banned the diesel
trade with Syria in the border areas, the local newspaper Daily
News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ankara will no longer grant visas to Syrian tanker drivers who
have been bringing diesel to Turkey in the last two months, the
paper quoted a statement of the Turkish Foreign Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Turkey made the decision in retaliation
for Syria's move to bar Turkish drivers from taking part in the
cross-border fuel trade.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear why Syria has banned Turkish drivers from the
cross-border transportation of diesel, which is allegedly produced
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors have been at odds due to a number of
differences, including the sharing of water resources and support
for anti-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, an energy-starving country, has to import crude oil and
oil products from neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
