<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overall Situation in China Excellent: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President
Jiang Zemin said here today that the overall situation in China is
excellent with its economic growth expected to be at nine percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
"China's economy is expected to grow at about eight percent in
the remaining years of this century and at about seven percent in
the first decade of the next century," Jiang said in his speech at
a dinner party hosted by Vancouver Mayor Philip Owen for the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told about 1,000 guests at the party that since the
launching of reform and opening-up in the late 1970s, China's
productive forces, overall national strength and people's living
standards have all improved significantly.
</P>
<P>
The volume of foreign trade, both import and export, will
hopefully exceed 310 billion U.S. dollars this year, and is
expected to reach 400 billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
This will promise a bigger market and greater opportunities to
the rest of the world to engage in economic exchanges and
cooperation with China, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party
of China last September drew a blueprint for China's reform,
opening-up and modernization drive towards the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"As required by reform and development, we will continue to
open the market steadily, speed up the process of opening up
infrastructures such as energy and communications and open up the
service sector such as banking and insurance with measured steps,"
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"We will also further improve trade and investment environment
and create conditions for equal competition between Chinese and
foreign-funded enterprises by protecting the rights and interests
of foreign-funded enterprises according to law," he said. "An
all-directional and multi-tiered opening-up pattern has basically
taken shape."
</P>
<P>
Jiang arrived here this morning for the 5th APEC informal
leadership meeting scheduled for Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
