<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Rural Areas on Alert for Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 24 (Xinhua) -- South African rural
areas have been warned of possible outbreak of cholera by the
country's health department.
</P>
<P>
Unless precautionary measures are taken, rural areas in the
country could experience a cholera outbreak similar to that in
neighboring Mozambique where at least 120 people have died, local
daily quoted health department officials as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Cholera has reportedly infected at least 2,700 people in
various parts of Mozambique and its capital Maputo.
</P>
<P>
The unidentified health officials said no special measures
were being implemented at ports of entry into South Africa as it
was impossible to detect the disease or prevent cholera-infected
people from entering the country.
</P>
<P>
Neil Cameron, national director of communicable disease
control, said that with conditions as they were in northern
KwaZulu Natal Province, Mpumalanga Province and Northern
Province, "we can expect cholera in the country."
</P>
<P>
The health department has sent a cholera alert to the three
provinces and a request to report any cases immediately.
</P>
<P>
Cameron said the oral vaccine provided only about 50 and 60
percent protection and did not stop the spread of the organism.
</P>
<P>
Cholera is usually transmitted via contaminated water, but can
also be conveyed by flies which contaminate food with infected
faeces.
</P>
<P>
People infected with the disease usually have symptoms of
severe diarrhoea, vomiting and rapid dehydration, which may
result in death if treatment is not timely.
</P>
<P>
The British Airways Travel Clinic in South Africa has run out
of the vaccine for the disease because of the unusually high
number of requests for the vaccine from tourists and locals since
cholera broke out in Mozambique two months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
