<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Percent of Zambian Children Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- About 10 to 15 percent of
Zambian children have disabilities and require active
intervention and specialized services in education, according to
Zambia Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper today quoted Willian Chanda, acting vice
chancellor for University of Zambia, as saying here on Sunday
that by 1995, 160,000 to 250,000 children of primary school going
age in the country had mental and physical disabilities and
needed special education.
</P>
<P>
He said this figure did not include mal-adjusted or mentally
disturbed children.
</P>
<P>
He said this scenario has led to the limitation of the
services for the identification, assessment and placement of such
children and in certain cases, virtual absence.
</P>
<P>
Currently, special education school provisions are still
inadequate from primary school to tertiary level, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 there were 31 special education institutions, 28 at
primary, one at secondary and two at tertiary levels, Chanda
noted.
</P>
<P>
There are also 80 special education units, of which 51 were at
the primary and 29 at the secondary school levels, he added.
</P>
<P>
Due to huge demands and the efforts made by the Zambia
Institute of Special Education, the university has introduced an
ambitious degree course in special education with assistance from
the Finnish and Zambian governments in the 1996-1997 academic
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dean of the school of education said that department is
offering many specialized services to people with disabilities
such as lessons in braille writing and speech correction among
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
