<HEADLINE> E. African Countries Plan to Establish Customs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Three east African countries
are conducting a study to set up a Customs Union in a bid to
harmonize customs tariffs among themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today quoted Cabinet Minister Nicholas Biwott
as saying that substantial progress had been made under the East
African Co-operation in the establishment of a regional policy
framework.
</P>
<P>
He told the just concluded East Africa Co-operation (EAC)
Joint Investment meeting held in Nairobi that the regional body
had embarked on a process of harmonization of investment codes in
member states of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The three governments are committed to the success of the
renewed co-operation, Biwott said, adding the three countries had
signed a tripartite double taxation agreement.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum of understanding was signed by the member
states' capital and security market authorities to promote the
development of stock markets in the region, the minister stated.
</P>
<P>
To encourage private and foreign investment between the three
countries, Biwott said, exchange-control liberalization and
abolition of import licensing measures had been put in place.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the ninth Permanent Tripartite Commission
of the EAC had been postponed due to preparations for the general
elections in Kenya next month.
</P>
<P>
However, permanent secretaries responsible for regional
cooperation from the three member states will meet as scheduled
starting today.
</P>
<P>
Among the issues to be discussed at the meeting is the signing
of a defense cooperation agreement envisaging joint security and
disaster handling operations among the three states.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the three chiefs of defense met in Arusha, northern
Tanzania, to draw up a draft memorandum of understanding to work
together on various defense related matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
