<HEADLINE> Regional Program to be Adopted to Combat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 24 (Xinhua) -- East African and Oceania
countries have drafted a Program of Action aimed at checking
land-based pollution activities, The East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper said that the program would be tabled for
adoption at an inter-governmental meeting scheduled for May next
year.
</P>
<P>
Julius Francis, director of the Zanzibar-based Institute of
Marine Sciences, told the paper that the program would provide
guidelines for a regional approach to combating pollution and
land degradation.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed at enhancing the quality of marine,
coastal and related fresh water environment in partnership with
communities which inhabit the coastal belt, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The director pointed out that the program would be designed to
fight land-based sources of harm such as domestic sewage, solid
domestic waste, agricultural run-off and industrial waste.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, he said, the authorities will construct
appropriate disposal sites, improve waste collection and disposal
systems as well as proper management of dumping sites.
</P>
<P>
The program was drawn up at a workshop held recently in
Zanzibar which was attended by representatives from Madagascar,
Comoros, Kenya, Tanzania, Mozambique and Seychelles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
