<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Popularize New Anti-Quake Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, November 24 (Xinhua) -- China has begun using a new
construction technology involving rubber cushioning to reduce
earthquake damage to buildings.
</P>
<P>
After repeated physical, chemical and mechanical tests, the
rubber-cushioned foundations of the buildings demonstrated a
strong bearing capacity and flexibility, said experts.
</P>
<P>
The rubber cushioning on building foundations will last 70
years, they said.
</P>
<P>
A steel-and-brick apartment building on Linghai Road in Shantou
employed the rubber cushions during its construction in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The eight-story building resisted a 1994 quake measuring 7.3 on
the Richter scale, which happened in the Taiwan Straits just 200
nautical miles from Shantou.
</P>
<P>
Apartment dwellers of the cushioned building said they hardly
felt the earthquake while other urban residents experienced heavy
shaking.
</P>
<P>
The rubber-cushioning technology could also be used in building
such projects as underground railways and bridges, experts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
