<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Introduce Non-Contaminating Wool Packs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- All wool presented for sale
after June 2000 must be inside special non-contaminating packs,
the Australian Wool Exchange Ltd. (AWEX) announced today.
</P>
<P>
The move follows overseas wool processor concerns about the
current HDPE (High Density Polyethylene) packs being a major
contributor towards wool contamination.
</P>
<P>
"The AWEX board has agreed that the Wool Exchange should use
its position to effect changes in the use of non-contaminating
packs while continuing to work with industry to overcome other
causes of contamination," AWEX Chairman John O'Neil said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
AWEX is a non-profit organization for Australian wool growers,
which, among other things, sets up the regulation for wool
package.
</P>
<P>
More than 3.5 million packs, all made overseas, are used
annually by the wool industry.
</P>
<P>
AWEX estimates 93 percent this season were made of HDPE.
</P>
<P>
Nylon wool packs are considered the only ones to offer
protection against contamination. But AWEX said this could change
over time.
</P>
<P>
The manufacture of HDPE packs is expected to stop by March 1999
with imports ceasing by June that year.
</P>
<P>
Expensive than HDPE packs, the nylon ones do not fray or pierce
as easily as HDPE packs, which can lead to stray fibers becoming
mixed up with the wool.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian School Girls Turned to Sex Victims by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Girl students in Monze, about
180 kilometers southwest of the Zambian capital, are becoming sex
victims in the hands of drug dealers, Times of Zambia reported
here today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted some parents with daughters at Rusangu
Secondary School and Charles Lwanga Teachers College in Monze as
complaining that their daughters are being used to serve truck
drivers after being drugged in some bars in town.
</P>
<P>
There is a well-organised syndicate which is ferrying girls
from their schools at midnight after offering them good money and
drugging them before handing them over to truck drivers,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The parents of the victims said something must be done to
correct the situation before many more girls get involved in
drug-trafficking and their education spoiled.
</P>
<P>
Adrenny Kanondo, headmistress of Rusangu Secondary School,
confirmed the matter, saying the issue is serious and needs the
immediate attention from the drug enforcement commission.
</P>
<P>
According to reliable information reaching her office and
proved by herself, she said, a number of girls are on the payroll
of some bar owners and that every weekend they are ferried in
cars at midnight to entertain truck drivers and other people.
</P>
<P>
It is also said that some bars in Monze are becoming transit
points of drugs from neighbouring countries, using innocent
children to sell on the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
