<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3,000 Australian Workers Evacuated from Steelworks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- At least one person was
injured and 3,000 workers were evacuated after major fires erupted
at a coastal steelworks 100 km south of Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
The meltdown of a power transformer has been blamed for
sparking a series of major fires which forced the evacuation today
of a Port Kembla steelworks owned by Australia's leading steel
producer BHP, or Broken Hill Pty. Co., and injured at least one
person, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Police Commander Bruce Newling from the Lake Illawarra patrol
told reporters that the emergency started in a power plant shortly
after 9 a.m. local time when a transformer melted down.
</P>
<P>
Newling said the meltdown caused a fire which then prompted a
power surge in a number of areas which resulted in a series of
fires throughout the plant including the coke ovens and two blast
furnaces.
</P>
<P>
A BHP spokesman said production resumed at the plant but it
would be a couple of days before it was working at full capacity.
</P>
<P>
"But we expect to be making steel before the day's out and
there will be no impact on our customers," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said a couple of workers on the waterfront had received
minor cuts and abrasions during the time of the fires, but it was
not yet confirmed whether they had been caused as a result of the
emergency.
</P>
<P>
The resources company said power was being progressively
returned to the plant via portable compressors and power plants.
</P>
<P>
The company said there was a major fault in the transformer or
high voltage power switch which interrupted power to much of the
plant.
</P>
<P>
The loss of power also triggered emergency close-down of the
blast furnaces and other key plant areas, BHP said.
</P>
<P>
The company said the situation was under control by 1 p.m.
local time and employees were beginning to return to various areas
of the plant after being evacuated earlier in the morning.
</P>
<P>
BHP Port Kembla plant manager George Edgar said it was still
too early to assess the cost of the fires.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
