<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Bankers Call for Stern Measures Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Institute of
Bankers (ZIB) has called for the creation of a statutory body to
deal with money laundering and other serious crimes more
effectively.
</P>
<P>
The proposed body should encompass the Drug Enforcement
Commission (DEC) and the Anti-Corruption Commission (ACC), ZIB
said, according to today's Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
ZIB also urged the government to make necessary amendments to
existing banking and financial services acts.
</P>
<P>
The resolutions passed at the just concluded money laundering
workshop held in Ndola in northern Zambia stipulated that stiff
penalties should be meted out for non compliance to both
individuals and institutions.
</P>
<P>
The seminar resolved that there should be an assurance of a
clear process of arbitration against victimization.
</P>
<P>
The act should have clauses to protect anti-money-laundering
officers so that their identity is kept secret.
</P>
<P>
The bankers resolved that former bankers with criminal records
should not be employed in financial institutions and that their
professional conducts should be approved by the ZIB.
</P>
<P>
ZIB pledged to set up continuous staff training on anti-money
laundering in order to be competent with international practising
standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
