<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Inflation to Hit Years' Low in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Israel's inflation is poised
to hit 29-year low in 1998, The Jerusalem Post today quoted
International Monetary Fund Vice-President Stanley Fischer as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said Israel's inflation could well fall to 7 percent in
1998, if current fiscal and monetary policy are maintained. The
last time Israel's inflation fell bellow 7 percent was in 1969.
</P>
<P>
"The 7 percent range is possible if they stay the course and
they're on track for that in 1998," said Fischer.
</P>
<P>
Israel's inflation this year is likely to reach 8.5 to 9.5
percent, with the government target set at 7 to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Responding to Fischer's 7 percent comment, Bank of Israel
Governor Jacob Frenkel said the government has set a 1998
inflation target of 7 to 10 percent and the central bank will work
to achieve this aim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
