<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Qaidam Basin Reports Progress in Oil-Gas Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Qaidam Basin on China's
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau has added 56 million tons to its proven
petroleum reserves over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai Provincial Petroleum Administration says that the
basin has 4.17 billion tons of petroleum reserves and over one
trillion cu.m. of gas reserves. It ranks fourth in China in
natural gas reserves, only after the Sichuan,
Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia, Tarim basins.
</P>
<P>
Song Kexian, deputy director of the administration, says that
China's strategy in the petroleum industry -- "stabilizing oil
output in the east and developing oil reserves in the west" has
allowed the Qaidam Basin to speed up oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
The administration has planned to find 600 million tons of
proven oil and gas reserves and produce three million tons of
crude oil and 800 million cu.m. of gas annually by 2000.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the Qaidam has spent one billion yuan
(about 830 million U.S. dollars) on oil and gas exploration, 25
percent more than the total for the Eighth Five-Year Plan
(1991-95) period. Only 10 percent of its total oil reserves and
five percent of natural gas have been verified in the basin,
according to Song.
</P>
<P>
"As more oil and gas reserves are verified, a number of related
industrial projects will be started, thus creating opportunities
for overseas investments, " he notes.
</P>
<P>
Two oil pipelines, with a total length of 300 km, and a
gas-burning power plant, have been completed, and 5,000 households
in the city of Golmud use gas for cooking. Work has also started
on a third gas pipeline, 280 km in length, and a 10,000-ton
methanol project in the Golmud Oil Refinery.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai Provincial Petroleum Administration has plans to
establish a joint-stock company and issue B-shares for overseas
investors. It will also build a gas pipeline from the basin to
Xining, capital of Qinghai Province, and a larger gas-burning
station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
