<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Defends Imposition of Visa Rule on Britons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's sovereign right to
make independent decisions on matters of national interest should
not be subject to debate, the Daily Nation today quoted a Kenyan
senior official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sammy Mbova, Permanent Secretary for Tourism and Wildlife
noted that decisions such as the imposition of visa requirements
for British travellers to Kenya were neither impulsive nor
punitive, but the culmination of exhaustive diplomatic
consultations between the relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
Mbova, who is leading a tourism promotion delegation
participating in the annual world travel market fair in London,
said that the new development should be accommodated in tourism
business operations without any reservations.
</P>
<P>
The new visa rule has been interpreted as a retaliation for
Britain's imposition of a visa requirement on Kenyans and other
east African citizens last year.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania was the first east African country to introduce visas
for visitors from Britain, and Uganda has recently been
considering a similar measure.
</P>
<P>
British tourists were reported as saying that the new rule was
"fair enough" as it is reciprocal.
</P>
<P>
A source from Kenya's tourism industry noted that despite the
opposition to the imposition of the visa rule by some
stakeholders in Kenya's tourism industry, the Kenyan government
was unlikely to reverse the decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
