<HEADLINE> Fujian Aims to Boost Maritime Transportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, November 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Fujian province, which
has 3,324 km of coastline, or 18.3 percent of the country's total,
plans to boost its cargo handling capacity at major ports.
</P>
<P>
It has 22 deep-water harbors, six of which now can handle
50,000-DWT ships, plus 20 ports equiped with 30 wharfs which has a
10,000-DWT capacity each.
</P>
<P>
The province handles 28 million tons of cargo a year and has
2,460 ships involved in marine transportation, which carries
600,000 containers a year.
</P>
<P>
The province is taking efforts to reinforce the ports of
Fuzhou, Xiamen, and Meizhou Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou and Xiamen ports have 200 million yuan (25 million
U.S. dollars) in fixed assets each and can handle up to 10 million
tons of cargo a year, earning 100 million yuan annually from
marine transportation.
</P>
<P>
Marine transportation helps the province's export-oriented
economy and also improves economic cooperation with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Growth of the marine industry is expected to exceed
that of the provincial economy as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
