<HEADLINE> China's Service Sector Gets More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The service sector in China's
interior areas have been attracting investors from Hong Kong and
overseas, according to a report from the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 and 1996, a quarter of the overseas investment in China
was in finance, infrastructure, transportation,
telecommunications, the retail business, foreign trade, real
estate, legal service, and accounting.
</P>
<P>
In finance, 142 overseas-funded banks have opened for business
in China with a combined turnover of 30 billion US dollars. Most
of them have made a profit within two years.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has encouraged overseas investors to get
involved in infrastructure projects and will continue to use loans
from international financial institutions and foreign governments
and to get investment from overseas businessmen. The build,
operat, and transfer method (BOT) will continue to be used.
</P>
<P>
Some telecommunications business will open to overseas
investors, including e-mail, electronic data interexchanges, and
fax services.
</P>
<P>
In the retail business, some joint retail ventures have been
allowed in 11 cities and special economic zones. Most of the
foreign partners were from Europe, the U.S., and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
