<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rodents Rampant in Tanzanian Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Large herds of rats are
ravaging maize and other crops in Turiani division in east
Tanzania's Morogoro region, posing serious threats to
agricultural output this season.
</P>
<P>
Peasants in Turiani, a major food production area, said on
Friday that numerous rodents emerged suddenly at the start of the
current rains, attacking crops in nearly 10 villages.
</P>
<P>
"I have planted two acres of maize for four times but all have
been eaten by rats. I'm tired," Kisimbo Mbwambo told Daily News.
</P>
<P>
The peasant said local people were surprised by the sudden
increase of the rodent population at the onset of rains.
</P>
<P>
"Usually they die in their holes when it rains. Now it is in
the opposite situation," he lamented.
</P>
<P>
Peasants sleeping in their farms during the night to guard
against baboons and wild pigs, now have to cover their feet for
fear of being bitten by rats.
</P>
<P>
Mbwambo, who have settled in Turiani for 25 years, said he has
never seen such a phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Other villagers say they have failed in killing the
crop-eating animals with chemicals or other traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
"We have tried to drown them in plastic containers filled with
water and food remains. You can kill 300 at a time but that has
not helped the situation," another peasant Emmanuel Mweta said.
</P>
<P>
The villages affected are all located in the lowland area east
of the Nguu mountains.
</P>
<P>
Omari Saidi, chairman of Lungo village, said villagers are
still looking for agricultural experts who can help solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Food shortage is imminent in the affected villages this year
despite the good rains this season, Saidi said, adding that two
types of rats were uprooting maize and rice seeds as well as
sugar canes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
