<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Say Further Dunhuang Research Is Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Some noted Chinese historians
are saying that research on the Dunhuang Grottoes needs to be
improved because of certain problems.
</P>
<P>
Duan Wenjie, director of the Dunhuang Research Institute in
northwest China's Gansu, says that the future does not look very
good if the research just stops at the textual stage, and that
there is not systematic program for the research, which is
currently dominated by personal interest instead of a larger plan.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhengyu, another Dunhuang expert, says that the number of
researchers in major Dunhuang research countries like France,
Japan and Russia is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Grottoes, on the silk road, in Gansu province in
northwest China, were discovered in 1900. Thousands of paintings,
manuscripts, statues, and other relics were found there and
then carted off by foreigners and are now scattered about in
foreign countries and in China.
</P>
<P>
Research on the grottoes has become very popular because it
provides important information about ancient religions, arts,
history, and China's connections with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Scholars suggest that better and more systematic research be
done to keep the study alive into the next century. Training more
young experts is the most important thing, they say, and there
should be extensive co-operation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, modern technology should be introduced to the
studies, and a publicity program developed to provide information
to the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
