<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Calls for Respect for Diversity in APEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President
Jiang Zemin today called for respect for the diversity of culture,
values and model of development among nations in seeking common
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"Only when we acknowledge differences, seek common ground while
putting aside differences, respect each other and cooperate for
mutual benefit can peace and stability be maintained in a region
and the world at large and common development and prosperity be
achieved," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech here at a dinner hosted by Vancouver Mayor
Philip Owen, Jiang said today's world is a diversified and
colorful one, in which all countries are independent and equal
members of the international community.
</P>
<P>
Peace and development have increasingly become the major themes
of our times, Jiang said. Countries are more closely interwoven
economically through exchanges.
</P>
<P>
"But it does not mean that there exists only one cultural
tradition, one value concept, or one model of development," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Jiang arrived here this morning for the 5th APEC informal
leaders' meeting scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said in the next two days, leaders from APEC members will
exchange views on how to further deepen and strengthen regional
economic and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
APEC, as the most important economic forum in this region, has
provided a good venue for members with different cultural
traditions and at varying development levels to strengthen
economic and technological cooperation through consultations on an
equal footing, he said.
</P>
<P>
After years of practice, APEC has formed its unique approach
which has been identified by the Manila meeting as "APEC
Approach", he said.
</P>
<P>
"This cooperative approach based on consensus and voluntarism
is in conformity with the trend of our times and the realities in
the Asia-Pacific region and strikes a balance between the rights,
interests and requirements of different partners," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
