<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Chain Stores to Emerge in Next Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Groups of giant chain stores
are likely to be created in the next five to 10 years in China,
the Ministry of Internal Trade disclosed over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The annual sales volume of each of these chains is expected to
exceed 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion U.S. dollars), according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Their participation will revolutionize China's traditional
commodity distribution by developing a fledging chain store
sector, said officials attending the ceremony to launch the China
Chain Store and Franchise Association (CCFA) here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter of congratulation on the establishment of the
association, Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said: "Practice has proved
that chain store management is an important means of realizing the
modernization of the commodity distribution industry and is the
main thrust for structural readjustment and in-depth reform for
the sector."
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of the management aim of chain store
businesses, which "is to bring convenience and benefit to the
people."
</P>
<P>
Chain store management has been introduced in early 1990s. With
its low-price and high-volume strategy, China's chain store sector
has grown rapidly. The trend has been warmly welcomed by
low-income families, which form the majority in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is to become the main-stream of the future development of
China's retail business, Li said.
</P>
<P>
China's chain store business fall broadly into seven categories
-- supermarkets, convenience stores, brand-name specialist shops,
department stores, snack counters, service centers and building
material shops.
</P>
<P>
"In 1994, there were 150 chain store companies with 2,500
outlets. But the number of companies had jumped to 1,000 with
14,000 outlets by the end of June this year." said Di Jiankai,
CCFA director and head of the Trade Administration Department of
the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Number of Ancient Bird Fossils Discovered in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, November 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 250 bird fossils
that date back 120 to 150 million years have been unearthed in the
western part of Liaoning Province in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Scholars from the U.S., Germany, Canada, and Britain have
visited the area in the past year, and the Fifth International
Conference on Birds and Evolution will be held in China in the
year 2000, with the Liaoning bird fossils high on the list of
discussion topics.
</P>
<P>
The latest discoveries belong to the late Jurassic Period and
the early Cretaceous Period of the Mesozoic Era, scholars say.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a large number of fish and plant fossils have been
unearthed in several counties.
</P>
<P>
No other place on earth has such a large fossil collection from
such a crucial period of change on earth that is preserved so
well, according to John Ostrom, Professor Emeritus of Yale
University, a well-known expert on ancient birds.
</P>
<P>
Scholars explain that today's Liaoning Province was an active
volcano region in ancient times, and gasses from volcanic
eruptions killed the birds and then instantly covered them with
volcanic ash.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1980s, farmers first found fish fossils in the area
and sold them secretly, but the later discovery of bird fossils
caught the local government's attention.
</P>
<P>
It's been estimated that many of the almost 1,000 ancient bird
fossils unearthed in the area have been sold abroad secretly,
according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have prohibited the collection or sale of
fossils and have set up a fossil preservation zone in a
two-sq.km. area, and are building a museum.
</P>
<P>
Scholars point out that the fossils will provide information
about the geography, climate, and environment of ancient times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
