<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Links Smoking to High Incidence of Throat Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, November 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 95 percent of
throat cancer patients are heavy smokers, which reinforces the
link between cigarettes and cancer, said a Chinese doctor.
</P>
<P>
"Heavy smokers are considered to be those who smoke more than
one pack of cigarettes a day," said Li Xiaoming, a 35-year-old
doctor at the No. 1 Clinical Hospital of the Bethune Medical
University in northeastern China's Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
Li said that ingredients in cigarettes such as nicotine and tar
curb the immune system and promote carcinogens. Smokers also run a
high risk of tumors in their respiratory systems, Li said.
</P>
<P>
"Those harmful elements in cigarettes can cause the split of
DNA, which will in turn result in the incidence of cancer," Li
said, adding that the "throat, which is more fragile to the
elements, is more likely to contract cancer."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
