<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist Finds That Early Emperor Lead A Strong Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist has found
evidence that Qinshihuang, China's first emperor, used a very
strong army to unite China for the first time, 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Feng Shenglin, 58, a biologist from Hunan Education College,
has been using modern anatomy for 10 years to study 8,000
terracotta figures unearthed near the emperor's tomb in the
Chinese city of Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
Feng's findings support what many historians believe that
Qinshihuang built one of the most powerful armies on the planet,
and a recently-published book says that 80 percent of the
sculptured soldiers are "healthy and strong", and 90 percent are
taller than ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
"It is obviously a robust army," Feng says. He is now in charge
of a 10-member group of researchers who are analyzing data from
the sculptures to find out how powerful the ancient army was.
</P>
<P>
Qinshihuang built China's first dynasty in 221 B.C after
several years of battles with six rival kingdoms in the Yellow and
Yangtze River valleys.
</P>
<P>
According to historical documents, millions of Qin soldiers
played a part in the reunification efforts. Many of them were then
used to help build the Great Wall after the dynasty was
established.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his death, the proud emperor duplicated his beloved
soldiers and officers in terracotta in hopes that the sculptures
would safeguard his underground palace.
</P>
<P>
The experts have also found that the terracotta warriors
represent almost all types of faces that can be found among
today's Chinese. Their findings also indicate that anatomy and art
were highly developed in China 2,000 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
