<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid Program Brings Hope to Tibetans in Poor Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Tibet Autonomous Region
has invested eight million yuan (one million US dollars) in a
comprehensive agricultural development zone in barren areas near
the Himalayas.
</P>
<P>
The development zone's 120 ha. of farmland, 120 ha.
of grasslands and 110 ha. of forests will provide employment for
some 300 poverty-stricken families in four neighboring townships with
a total population of 1,400 people.
</P>
<P>
The zone covers 13,000 sq.km. in Tingri County, Tibet's poorest
county.
</P>
<P>
Despite extensive wastelands, the county has abundant water,
solar energy and mineral resources. Tingri, a country with a
poverty-stricken population of some 30 percent, has failed to
realize economic development due to severe weather conditions and
backward infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The first training course for poor people was introduced to the
county two years ago. However, the county plans to reach the
nation's poverty relief standards by the end of 1998, according to
a local official.
</P>
<P>
Tingri will allocate over 7.37 million yuan for poverty relief
and will complete all approved development projects, including
population relocation and construction of water treatment
facilities. The county will also establish a loan fund of 12
million yuan, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He added that the county is currently focusing on large-scale
irrigation projects and the reclamation of low-yield land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
