<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Russia to Promote Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin arrived here today for a three-day visit to Vietnam
aimed at promoting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Prime Minister Pan Van Khai is scheduled to hold a
welcome ceremony at the president's residence before his formal
talks with the visiting Russian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The promotion of bilateral economic and trade cooperation is
said to be one of the topics of their talks.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, President of Vietnam Tram Duc Luong will meet
Chernomyrdin, sources from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides will sign several accords on economic and trade
cooperation this evening.
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi, General Secretary of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of Vietnam, is scheduled to meet the visiting
Russian prime minister tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin is the highest-ranking official from Russia to
visit Vietnam since the disintegration of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the then Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet visited
Russia.
</P>
<P>
In the 1970s and 1980s, the former Soviet Union was the largest
source of foreign aid to Vietnam and its largest export market as
well.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of the Soviet Union brought about a sharp decline
in Vietnamese-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been striving to restore their bilateral
ties in recent years. 
</P>
