<HEADLINE> China-Registered Ship Sinks in Malaysia's Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 24 (Xinhua) -- A China-registered
general cargo ship sank in the North Port, Port Klang, Malaysia,
last night with no casualties reported.
</P>
<P>
All 25 crew members on board the ship "M.V. Antai" managed to
escape from the sinking ship and are now staying at the Klang Port
Authority (KPA) club house, according to KPA commercial manager
Chong Choon Yin today.
</P>
<P>
The 15,000 ton deadweight vessel arrived from the port of
Xingang with 8,485 tons of fertilizer and chemicals to be unloaded
at Port Klang, some 40 kilometers west of here, and Pasir Gudang,
Johor, some 370 kilometers southeast of here.
</P>
<P>
The KPA official said there were still 4,500 tons of fertilizer
to be discharged at Port Klang when the vessel sank at 10:30 pm.
It was raining and there was no stevedoring work in progress at
the time.
</P>
<P>
Chong said the cause of the accident is being investigated.
</P>
