<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Plans to Build 2,500 Cyclone Shelters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
taken up a massive program for the construction of 2,500 cyclone
shelters in phases in a bid to minimize the loss of life and
property from tropical cyclones, the national news agency BSS
reported today.
</P>
<P>
As of today, about 1,000 cyclone shelters have been built, out
of a target of 1,200 set for the first phase, with help from
friendly countries, international voluntary organizations and
non-governmental organizations, BSS quoted MH Khan Chowdhury, a
disaster preparedness specialist, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's entire coastal belt of 710 kilometers is exposed
to the potential danger of cyclones.
</P>
<P>
Since the country gained independence in 1971, 3,931 kilometers
of coastal embankments have been built by the Bangladesh Water
Development Board under 435 projects to protect coastal land from
inundation by tidal waves and storm surges, Chowdhury said in a
paper on "Cyclone, the Cyclone Warnings and their Dissemination:
Bangladesh Perspective."
</P>
<P>
Killer-severe cyclones develop along the country's coasts with
75 percent chances strictly from April 15 to June 15 and from
September 15 to December 15, he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
