<HEADLINE> India's Inflation Continues to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The decline in India's
inflation continued for the fourth week in succession with the
annual rate of inflation dropping to 3.2 percent for the week
ended November 8, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the inflation rate fell by 0.03 percentage
points from 3.23 percent in the previous week and 6.47 percent
during the corresponding week last year.
</P>
<P>
The wholesale price index (WPI) for all commodities (base
1981-82=100) fell by 0.1 percent from the week before to 329.3.
</P>
<P>
Inflation has slumped by about one percentage point in the last
four weeks alone.
</P>
<P>
Economists here have suggested that the persistent fall,
despite recent hikes in the prices of petroleum products and rail
freight charges, may be due to the slackening of demand in the
sluggish Indian economy.
</P>
<P>
Though analysts have predicted an upturn in inflation in the
second half of the year, signs of any upward movement in inflation
is yet to be sighted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
