<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Anti-drug Drive Hurt by Economic Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The current economic slowdown
has not frustrated the drug trade in Thailand but hurt local
police efforts to fight drug, a senior Thai police officer said.
</P>
<P>
Drug dealers have cut drug prices to maintain their market in
Thailand as the country is undergoing an economic slowdown,
Thailand's Narcotics Suppression Bureau Commander Noppadol
Somboonsap said at a seminar here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An amphetamine pill which used to cost 120 baht (4.8 U.S.
dollars) now was sold at 50-70 baht (1.2-1.7 dollars), the Thai
drug suppression head was quoted as saying by local newspapers
today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, amphetamines have emerged as a popular alternative
to the expansive heroin in Thailand now, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Thai police's drive against drug was
weakened as the government cut its budget due to the economic
slowdown, Noppadol said.
</P>
<P>
The budget for drug suppression shrank to merely 17 million
baht (0.4 million dollars) compared with the more than 100 million
baht (4 million dollars) in the past, he said.
</P>
<P>
Police could not launch strong campaigns with such limited
funds, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
