<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irrigation Project in NW China Provides Water for Arid Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Yindaruqin Irrigation
Project in northwest China's Gansu Province is playing an
increasing big role in promoting local economic development.
</P>
<P>
The project, which began partial operation in October of 1995,
has helped farmers increase local grain output by 10 million
kilograms and forest areas by more than 660 hectares. The improved
environment has attracted 35,000 farmers to settle in the
irrigated areas.
</P>
<P>
The project was constructed to divert water from the Datong
River in Qinghai Province to Qinwangchuan Plain, about 60
kilometers away from Lanzhou, capital of Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
With feeder, main and branch canals totaling 884 kilometers --
half the distance of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal -- the
project has been called the longest "underground canal" in China.
</P>
<P>
"The townships of Dongshan, Xicao and Shuping of Yongdeng
County benefited from the irrigation project first," said Gu
Qihao, chief engineer of the project.
</P>
<P>
The main part of the project was completed in 1995. It provides
water for 14,000 hectares of cultivated farmland, an increase of
6,000 hectares from the 1995 figure of 8,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the project, the Qinwangchuan area got a
per-hectare grain yield of 5,250 kilograms in 1995, six times that
of previous years.
</P>
<P>
The region has upgraded 866 hectares of land into high-yielding
farmland, and improved 2,000 hectares of low-yielding land. As
many as 730,000 trees have been planted. An area of 2,660 hectares
has been afforested, with profitable orchards occupying 265
hectares.
</P>
<P>
When the project goes into full operation, it is expected to
irrigate 57,300 hectares of farmland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
