<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Garment Industry on Verge of Closing Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The garment industry, a
major foreign currency earner for Nepal, is on the verge of
closing down due to lack of clear-cut policies of the government,
newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Nepal's ready-made garments are five percent more
expensive than those made in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Sri
Lanka has led to a slackness in exports, the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
Following the establishment of the garment industry in the
1980s, the number of garment factories reached 1,300 in 1990, but
less than 300 are now operating in the country, the newspapers
said.
</P>
<P>
Ready-made garments worth 60 million rupees (about 1 million
U.S. dollars) were exported in the last fiscal year which ended on
July 14, but the very beginning of this fiscal year witnessed a
slump, the Nepal Garment Industries Association said.
</P>
<P>
The government's policy of distributing quotas for setting up
garment factories is much blamed for the slump, the association
said, adding that many factories receiving quotas are doing other
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on management of garment factories Sunday,
Nepali Commerce Minister Prakash Chandra Lohani said that the
government is committed to tackling the problems facing the
garment industry.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's garment industry imports raw materials from India,
China, Indonesia and Pakistan and exports ready-made garments to
the United States, Germany, France and England.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
