<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian Prime Minister Visits Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime Minister Gyula
Horn arrived here today and went into talks with his Austrian
counterpart Viktor Klima,
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Horn briefed Klima about the referendum in
Hungary on its entry into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO).
</P>
<P>
Hungary held the referendum on November 16 to decide if the
country should join the NATO. Among the 49 percent of eight
million eligible voters who took part in the referendum, 85
percent voted for Hungary's participation.
</P>
<P>
Klima, the Austrian chancellor, reaffirmed at a press
conference after the meeting that a referendum on joining the NATO
would be held in Austria only under some conditions.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian government should first of all propose that
Austria join the military alliance if and when a unanimous
decision is made by the Social Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Then the Austrian National Council should adopt a resolution
calling for Austria's participation in the NATO.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Klima and Horn announced at the conference that the
prime ministers of Austria, Hungary and the Czech Republic will
meet in Budapest in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
Austria and Hungary do not want to isolate the Czech Republic,
nor exclude it from European integration, they said.
</P>
<P>
Horn stressed that at the meeting, the three government heads
will also discuss measures to fight organized crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
