<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Mountainous Area (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yimeng used to be known as a blocked off area with no
transportation and bad natural conditions. So, the local
government has helped farmers improve the infrastructure in the
past few years. By now, 9,800 km of road have been built, 70,000
water conservation projects constructed, 60,000 hectares of
land at mountainside reclaimed, and 60 million fruit trees planted.
</P>
<P>
Production of grains, oil-bearing crops, vegetables, fruits,
building materials and animal husbandry have now become major
industries of the local people. Pingyi County in the area has
become China's biggest honeysuckle producer and Changshan County
a major vegetable base in southern Shandong.
</P>
<P>
Large enterprises and wholesales markets have also mushroomed
in the area. The Linyi Wholesale Market does 15 billion yuan (1.76
billion US dollars) in business annually, making it one of China's
top five free markets.
</P>
<P>
The central and provincial governments have provided 860
million yuan, helping people in the Yimeng Mountain areas
alleviate proverty over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The GDP of Yimeng was 37 billion yuan last year, five times the
1984 figure. Per capita net income of the seven poorest counties
in the area was 1,900 yuan, compared to 150 yuan in 1984.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Launches Probe into Finance Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand has
launched a probe into a local finance firm, accusing its
executives of fraud and mismanagement, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Sunday, the Thai central bank said that
Mahatun Finance Co. was found to have extended loans from August
to October in a dishonest way.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has sacked three top executives of the firm,
which is one of the 33 finance firms currently still operating in
Thailand, and appointed two regulators and one outsider to
investigate its accounting books.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also ordered freezing the assets of the three
top executives for 180 days, while requesting the Police
Department to prohibit any executives of the firm from leaving
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Regulators were forced to take urgent action to correct the
company's financial position and prevent damage to the public
interest, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The move is the first action taken by the central bank using
its expanded power under the six financial reform decrees passed
last month, which authorize the central bank to sack directors and
executives of a company without calling a shareholders' meeting.
</P>
<P>
It is also the first action taken by the bank against the 33
finance firms that it announced healthy after suspending the
operation of 58 finance firms in June and August due to their
funds problems.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that the firm's operation would continue
as normal and depositors and creditors would remain under the full
protection of the government.
</P>
<P>
Central bank officials said that the measure taken against the
firm was not due to the firm's finance position but the unethical
and illegal behavior of its top executives, who reportedly used
falsified documents to obtain loans from the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Mahatun Finance has a registered capital of merely 150 million
baht (3.75 million U.S. dollars). Thailand's Association of
Finance Companies said that the firm reported its net assets at
949.5 million baht (about 38 million dollars) in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
