<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Currency Devalued Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The exchange rate of the
Bangladeshi currency taka against the U.S. dollar has been
adjusted downwards by 0.45 taka or one percent with effect from
today, announced the Bangladesh Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank rate of Bangladesh, the floor interest rate on which
it lends to the commercial banks, has been re-fixed at eight
percent from the current 7.5 percent, also effective today,
according to a separate announcement of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Bank's buying and selling rates for the
greenback with authorized dealer banks will now stand at 45.30 and
45.60 taka per dollar respectively, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh's currency was last devalued on October 24 with
buying rate of 44.85 taka and selling rate of 45.15 taka per
dollar. The spread between the buying and selling rates was fixed
at 0.30 taka from the earlier 0.20 taka.
</P>
<P>
The new buying-selling middle rate has been revised to 45.45
taka from the earlier 45.00 taka per dollar.
</P>
<P>
With the latest downward adjustment, the Bangladeshi currency
has been devalued for the 11th time in less than one and a half
years of the present government.
</P>
<P>
The new bank and exchange rates were announced at a time when
the country's foreign exchange reserves came down to an
"uncomfortable" low while the credit to the private sector was
growing over the target, local newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
The inflation, which was almost static at a low level for a
long time, showed an alarming rise with the expansion of the
private sector credit, prompting the authorities to go for the
dual-strategy, newspapers added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
