<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovak Foreign Minister Visits Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, November 23 (xinhua) -- Slovakia's Foreign Minister
Zdenka Kramplova arrived here Sunday for an official visit to
Bulgaria and said the two countries can cooperate more actively
and more fruitfully in the future.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Bulgarian Chamber of Commerce and Industry
Sunday evening, Kramplova said fine institutional conditions have
been created to promote two-way trade.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Slovak Republic and Bulgaria traded 29.4 million
U.S. dollars' worth of goods, of which 19.7 million were Slovak
exports to, and 9.7 million were imports, from Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
However, she expressed her country's dissatisfaction at the
bilateral trade since the implementation of a free trade agreement
on January 1, 1996. The trade volume even dropped in
January-September 1997 compared with the same period a year ago,
she said.
</P>
<P>
"The Slovak Republic is interested in the entry of Slovak
companies into the Bulgarian market and is pleased to find that
Slovak companies are already starting to show some interest," she
said.
</P>
<P>
So far, 12 Bulgarian-Slovak joint ventures have been registered
in Slovakia and 10 in Bulgaria. She also argued in favour of a
reactivation of the joint economic commission.
</P>
<P>
On Monday Kramplova and her Bulgarian counterpart, Nadezhda
Mihailova, will meet to discuss questions concerning the two
countries' European and Euro-Atlantic integration and bilateral
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
