<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Agrees to Lower 1998 Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
bowed to the International Monetary Fund (IMF)'s judgment and
agreed to lower its economic growth targets for 1998, including a
revision of vital macroeconomic indicators.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine negotiating panel agreed to lower the expected
gross national product (GNP) growth to 5.0 to 5.3 percent from a
high of 6.0 to 6.5 percent target earlier presented to the IMF,
Manila Bulletin today quoted government sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government also agreed to raise the inflation rate and
interest rate targets for next year, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
From a relatively low scenarios of 6.0 percent, the average
inflation rate for the whole of 1998 now was pegged at a range of
6.5 to 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The average yield of the bellwether 91-day Treasury Bills
(T-bills) was moved up to a range of 13 to 15 percent from an
earlier assumption of 13.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government panel and an IMF review mission
earlier reached an impasse in their disagreement over the
country's economic growth figures for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines insisted that GNP growth for the next year
could hit 6.5 to 7.5 percent while the IMF said it should expect
only 4 to 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said this would be a more realistic target considering
the full effect of the continuing depreciation of regional
currencies would be felt only in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also found the government's projections of inflation
rate and interest rate in 1998 to be too low.
</P>
<P>
The IMF review mission left the country last Wednesday without
firming up the macroeconomic targets for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
The sources admitted that the revision was made to reflect the
continuing currency turmoil in the region and possible ill-effects
of the EL Nino phenomenon which is already causing a prolonged
drought in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the Philippines and the IMF still disagree on the
government's fiscal position and the macroeconomic projections for
1997, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
