<HEADLINE> China, South Korea Commit to Four-Party Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and South Korean Foreign Minister
Yoo Chong-ha today pledged more efforts in the four-party talks on
the Korean Peninsula for peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers, who came here for meetings of the Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum, expressed their
satisfaction at the progress made in the four party talks, a
Chinese foreign ministry spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea, South Korea, China,
and the U.S. Friday agreed to begin negotiations on the Korean
Peninsula next month in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman quoted Qian as saying that China believes an
early establishment of a peace mechanism on the peninsula through
the four party talks is in the interests of all the sides
concerned, and conducive to the peninsula's peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
China, welcoming the progress achieved so far in the talks,
will continue its close cooperation with all sides, and play a
constructive role for more fruitful results of the talks, Qian was
quoted as telling Yoo.
</P>
<P>
Expressing their satisfaction at bilateral ties, Qian and Yoo
stressed that their countries will continue to work together to
deepen and expand economic and trade cooperation, which is
mutually beneficial.
</P>
<P>
China and South Korea established diplomatic relations five
years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
