<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Companies in Bangkok Close Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 630 registered
companies in Bangkok with a total registered capital of 1.585
billion baht (41.7 million U.S. dollars), closed operation last
month due to economic slowdown, according to the Thai Commerce
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, only 357 firms closed their doors.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 638 companies closed, 101 were from the troubled
property and real estate sector. Each firm had a minimum
registered capital of 500 million baht (13 million dollars), a
source at the ministry was quoted today by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors that recorded closures include transport,
construction, consumer products and beauty salons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People in East China Mountainous Area Getting Better Life (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Early in the morning twilight,
58-year-old Li Changxue, a village official, leaves his home in
Badayu Village in east China's Shandong Province and hurries over to
the highway near the village to co-ordinate business at
the local fruit market.
</P>
<P>
Fruits traders from near and far come with their trucks and
wait for hours for buyers from the village in the Yimeng Mountains,
where 180 households used to depend heavily on farming.
</P>
<P>
Most of the villagers were poor because of water
shortages, and many went out to beg just to survive. Li himself
worked very hard, but could not feed his three children.
</P>
<P>
However, the reform and opening-up policy of China has changed
things. The government of Mengyin county, where Li lives,
restructured agriculture by encouraging farmers to plant fruit trees
on mountain slopes.
</P>
<P>
As a result, per capita income of the villagers is now 3,000
yuan and Li' family now earns over 30,000 yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
The change in Li's family epitomizes that in the Yimeng
Mountains, where 9.7 million people live.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income was below 150 yuan in Yimeng Mountain areas in
1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
