<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Reveals Urban Preferences for Entertainment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- A recent poll shows that
China's urban dwellers spend most of their spare time on
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
About 46.9 percent of those surveyed chose "seeing films" as
their favorite entertainment activity. while 34.4 percent liked
"watching TV."
</P>
<P>
Beijing's Horizon Research Group organized the survey of 1,500
urban residents between 18 and 60 in Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou,
Chongqing and Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
Reading, listening to cassettes, watching VCDs, playing
karaoke, listening to radio broadcasts and dancing also were
listed as favorite activities, the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
However, people's interests varied by city. Beijing and
Chongqing residents liked watching TV best, but showed less
interest in going to the cinema; Guangzhou residents loved seeing
films and going to amusement parks, but were less enthusiastic
about reading and listening to music; Shanghai residents favored
listening to the radio, going to theaters and playing computer
games.
</P>
<P>
Besides entertainment, a growing number of urban residents
listed physical-fitness exercise as a favorite spare-time
activity. Half chose walking and others listed badminton, table
tennis, basketball and football, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Overwhelming Majority of the ordinary residents did not list
golf or bowling because of their relatively high cost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
