<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian, Albright Meet in Vancouver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen met here today with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, their seventh meeting in a
year.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Qian said Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
state visit to the U.S. last month was very successful as both
sides agreed to establish a constructive strategic partnership for
the 21st century, Chinese diplomatic sources told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The achievement is not only in the interests of a long-term,
stable and healthy development of Sino-U.S. relations, but also
conducive to world peace and stability, Qian was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Albright told Qian that Jiang's visit is very successful since
it established a framework and set a target for the U.S.-China
relations, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton is expecting to meet Jiang again,
Albright told Qian, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed his hope that the two sides will implement the
agreements reached between the two sides during Jiang's visit to
strengthen bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also discussed China's entry into the
World Trade Organization (WTO). They said they hope their
countries will conclude negotiations on the issue as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they promised to expand cooperation in all areas,
including regional and international affairs, in accordance with
the common views Jiang and Clinton shared during their meeting.
</P>
<P>
The four-party talks on the Korean Peninsula, issues about
Iraq, and Climate Change Treaty negotiations were also discussed,
the Chinese sources said, with giving further details.
</P>
<P>
Qian and Albright arrived here last week to attend the meetings
of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
