<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou to Offer Affordable Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Guangzhou Municipal
Government will switch its attention to its "comfort housing"
project in 1998 to provide shelter to those with scarce living
space, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The city has provided about 39,000 flats to the 26,000 families
whose living space is less than five square meters per person and
those who earn less than the city's average annual income of
13,634 yuan (about 1,642 U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, more than 80 percent of them prefer buying flats in
the "comfort housing" project, so the government has decided to
start the project early next year, said Jin Yiguo, assistant
director of the city's property administration bureau.
</P>
<P>
In the next three years, the city will raise about 1.8 billion
yuan (about 216.87 million U.S.dollars) each year to construct
several blocks consisting of multi-storeys or high-rises, with the
floor space of each condominium ranging from 50 to 75 square
meters, he said.
</P>
<P>
The project will cover 3.72 million square meters, 20 percent
of the building space of 18.6 million square meters to be erected
as part of the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The prices of the multi-storey building will be between 1,900
yuan (about 228.9 U.S.dollars) and 2,200 yuan (about 265.1
U.S.dollars) per square meter, while the prices of the high-rise
buildings will range from 2,800 yuan (about 337.30 U.S.dollars) to
3,100 yuan (about 373.5 U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of the residential buildings in the project will
be directly sold, 10 percent of them through bank mortgages and
the remaining 10 percent will be set aside for rent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTA Tour to Make Changes for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 23 (Xinhua) -- WTA Tour CEO Anne Person
Worcester said on Sunday that the 1998 women's tennis tour will
add six more tournaments, increase prize money and try to head off
a pleyrs coup launched earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Worcester, who decided not to renew her contract with the WTA
Tour to spend more time with her family, said the tour does not
recognize a recent attempt by a number of mid-ranked players to
take over the WTA Player Association.
</P>
<P>
Tour players Linda Harvey Wild of the United States, Karin
Kschwendt of Luxembourg and Patricia Hy Boulais of Canada
spearheaded a revolt at the Chicago tournament earlier this month
aimed at improving the stature of rank-and-file players.
</P>
<P>
The WTA Tour has received a temporary restraining court order
against the move, in which three members were removed from the
player association's executive board and replaced by associates
sympathetic to mid-ranked players' objectives.
</P>
<P>
For 1998, the women's tour will have six new lower level, Tier
III and Tier IV events. These tournaments will take place in
Bogota; Makarska, Croatia; Istanbul; Boston, Seoul and Bali,
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The new Croatian tournament is a doubles only event.
</P>
<P>
Tour prize money will increase from slightly over 38 million
U.S. dollars this year to over 40 million U.S. dollars in 1998.
The four Grand Slams, the Chase Championships and Tier I events in
Moscow, Key Biscayne and Indian Wells will offer in excess of one
million U.S. dollars in prize money for the women.
</P>
<P>
After an extensive search for Worcester's replacement failed to
find a likely candidate for the CEO position, the WTA Tour's Board
of Directors have agreed to change the approval procedure for the
position.
</P>
<P>
Instead of a unanimous 10-0 board vote, only seven votes of
approval are needed to appoint a new CEO.
</P>
<P>
If a new CEO is not found by January 1, Bausch &AMP; Lomb
Tournament Director Bob Arrix will temporarily manage the tour's
day-to-day operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
