<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist City Improves Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The port city of
Qinhuangdao, a popular spot for visitors to northern China's Hebei
Province, is striving to create a sound environment for developing
tourism.
</P>
<P>
The city has established bird sanctuaries, coastal protection
zones, a wild animal zoo and forest reserves in its coastal and
northern mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
The city launched "Afforestation Year" in 1996 and, so far,
more than 100 million yuan (12.5 million U.S. dollars) has been
spent to plant more than 600,000 trees. Per capita grassland
occupation stands at 5.73 square meters and the grassland coverage
rate is 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to improve the natural environment have paid off,
officials say. Beidaihe, a well-known summer resort, has become a
haven for birds. A total of 405 species of birds, or one-third of
the country's total, have been found in this region.
</P>
<P>
To wipe out pollution, Qinhuangdao has focused its attention on
developing environmentally friendly industries and harnessing
polluting enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Improvements in the environment has facilitated the development
of the tourism industry and opened the province wider to the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
During the January-August period, domestic and overseas
visitors exceeded six million, with an economic returns of more
than two billion yuan (250 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Up to date, the city has approved 848 overseas-funded
enterprises, with 1.88 billion U.S. dollars in contracted overseas
funding. More than 230 overseas-funded firms, now in operation,
have produced 37 percent of the city's total industrial output
value.
</P>
<P>
The city's gross domestic product reached 20.12 billion yuan
(2.5 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, 3.3 times that of 10 years
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient City Protecting Old Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Many aging trees are being
placed into protection programs, including a 150-year-old cypress
in Xi'an, capital city of northwest China's Shaanxi province,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A fence was placed around the tree, situated on a business
street in the ancient city, the starting point of the world-famous
Silk Road, last week.
</P>
<P>
An engraved plate with an inscription asking passers-by to help
protect the cypress was also attached to the tree, reported the
paper.
</P>
<P>
In all, 632 trees, each more than 100 years old, will be
protected, with fences and plates, in Xi'an by the end of the
year, an official with Xi'an Municipal Afforestation Office said.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an is one of China's six ancient capitals, dating back
thousands of years. It has many old trees, considered "green
cultural relics".  
</P>
</TEXT>
