<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steggal Wins Women's Slalom in Utah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 23 (Xinhua) -- French-born Zali Steggall
of Australia claimed the victory in the first slalom of the season
when she won the women's World Cup race in Park City, Utah on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Steggall, who grew up in Sydney after moving Down Under as a
child, now trains in Morzine, France, while racing under
Australian colours.
</P>
<P>
She held onto a lead from the morning run down the Clementine
course flagged with 54 gates to post victory in one minute 36.30
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Swede Ylva Nowen finished second on 1:37.08, while Claudia
Riegler, an Austrian who changed nationalties and races for New
Zealand, put two Antipodeans on the podium with third in 1:37.35.
</P>
<P>
The victory was the first for an Aussie woman at the World Cup
level. Steven Lee won a men's super-giant slalom at Furano,
Japan, 1985, while in 1970 Malcom Milne won the Val d'Isere
downhill.
</P>
<P>
The historic win did not change the order in the overall World
Cup standings, where Italy's Deborah Compagnoni, who failed to
finish the first run, and German Martina Ertl are first and second.
</P>
<P>
The women's World Cup continues this week with a super-giant
slalom and a parallel slalom starting Thursday in Mammoth
Mountain, California. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
