<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Sugar Maker Begins to Net Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Tongyi (Unified) Sugar
Manufacturing Co. Ltd of Nanning, capital of south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, has started to net profits 13 months after
its estalishment in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Nanning had six state-owned sugar refineries, four
of which had losses in 1995. So the city government combined
the six into the Nanning Tongyi. By the end of August
this year, it had net a profit of 2.33 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The new company presses 20,000 tons of sugarcane a day and
produces 200,000 tons of sugar a year, making it China's biggest
sugar maker. It still had 7.62 million yuan in losses in 1996
because of management and market problems.
</P>
<P>
To halt this trend, the company improved controls on technical
development and equipment to reduce expenditures, and on
marketing, and had a management shake-up in the six factories.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the company got an average of 4,130 yuan per ton
of sugar this year, 120 yuan more than last year. By mid-August,
12,000 tons of stockpiled sugar had been sold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin's Human History Dates Back 1,000 Years Earlier Than Known </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The latest archeological
findings suggest that the human history of Tianjin, the largest
coastal city in northern China, date back 7,000 years ago, a
millennium earlier than previously believed.
</P>
<P>
In March, a farmer found remnants of earthenware in Jixian
County in the northern region of Tianjin, drawing attention from
local governments.
</P>
<P>
Pottery, boneware and stoneware were unearthed at the 3,000
Square meter site. Archeologists said their findings include
household implements, tools of production and ancient religious
instruments which are from the early Neolithic age.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Wengang, an archeologist participating in the excavation
at the site, said the findings are different from either the
Yangshao culture of central China or the Hongshan culture of
northern China.
</P>
<P>
The new findings are of great value to the study of the history
of the city and northern China, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the city's cultural relics department has taken
measures to protect the site. The study of the relics is still
under way.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
