<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Provides More Jobs for Handicapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Eastern China's Shandong
Province has provided jobs for 1.4 million handicapped people, or
75 percent of those who are employable.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, the province plans to increase that to 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
In recent years Shandong has issued several regulations to
create a favorable environment for the employment of the
province's two million handicapped residents.
</P>
<P>
Despite an increase in the number of laid-off workers, 75 labor
service organizations and 44 training centers have been built to
professionally train 75,000 handicapped people.
</P>
<P>
Some cities even allot compulsory quotas for the number of
handicapped employees to relevant enterprises to increase job
opportunities for the handicapped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book Outlines Tibetans' Role in Qinghai Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The "History of Tibetans in
Qinghai" has been published in northwestern China's Qinghai
Province.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say the book is a comprehensive achievement in
Qinghai's Tibetan history study.
</P>
<P>
Written by Chen Guangguo, a professor from Qinghai Institute
for Ethnic Minorities, the book describes the historical
development of Tibetans in Qinghai and important tribes of the
Tibetan people in such aspects as history, religious beliefs,
ethnic traditions and local rules.
</P>
<P>
Tibetans in Qinghai have contributed a lot to the creation of a
unique culture together with residents of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, Sichuan, Gansu and Yunnan provinces, according to the book.
</P>
<P>
Some scholars said the book is valuable for the study of the
history of the Tibetan people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
