<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baby Whales Returned to Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Five baby whales, who
apparently became lost in the tide and mistakenly swam to the
shore, have been returned to the sea with the help of an aquatic
products department and fishermen in Taizhou, eastern China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based "China Oceanic News" reported that the whales
were caught by local fishermen when they were stranded on the
shore. Each of them weighed 40-50 kilograms with a sea-blue back
and a circular spouting hole on the head.
</P>
<P>
The whales, about 1.2 meters long, reportedly made crying
sounds. Experts believed that they were newborn whales.
</P>
<P>
The Taizhou aquatic products bureau brought the five whales
into deep ditches on the shore, and kept them alive for several
days. After the baby whales recovered sufficiently, they were
returned to the sea.
</P>
<P>
This was the first report ever of stranded whales in Taizhou.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Meteorological Observatory in China Repaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The oldest civilian
meteorological observatory in China, built in 1916 in Nantong, has
been renovated.
</P>
<P>
The Junshan Meteorological Observatory, built with financial
support from industrialist Zhang Jian, provided weather forecast
service for residents in Jiangsu Province, east China.
</P>
<P>
The observatory gained worldwide fame through business with 40
other countries.
</P>
<P>
However, it was shut down after being severely damaged by
bombings during the War of Resistance Against Japan (1937-1945).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
