<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-23 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King Hussein Meets with Iraqi Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 23 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan met
today with visiting Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz at the
Royal Palace to discuss Iraqi standoff with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's official news agency Petra reported that in the
90-minute meeting, the king stressed the need "to take all
necessary steps that will ensure the speedy lifting of sanctions
and the suffering of the brotherly Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
The meeting came as U.N. arms inspectors returned to Baghdad
and resumed their regular work after Russia promised Iraq to seek
a rapid lifting of the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. arms inspectors working with the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) on dismantling Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction resumed their normal work in Iraq from Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This followed the diplomatic solution to a three-week standoff
between the U.N. and Iraq, which expelled U.S. inspectors in order
to draw world attention to its demand for the lifting of the
crippling U.N.sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The teams returned to Iraq Friday after Baghdad had officially
told the U.N. Security Council its agreement to the resumption of
the work of UNSCOM with all its members, including the Americans,
taking part.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Aziz, who arrived here Saturday, called for
all the Arab countries to resume flights to Iraq as soon as
possible, as a way to help Baghdad defuse the influence of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Iraq urged the resumption of Arab airlines to Iraq as there was
not a decision from the United Nations yet forbidding such
flights, Aziz told a group of Jordanian politicians and media
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
