<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-23 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Ready to Resume Navigation to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Minister of
Transport Al Binu Akul Akul said here today that navigation will
be resumed between Sudan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Akul made the remarks when speaking to reporters before leaving
for Cairo to participate in the African Transport Ministers
Conference due to be held on November 24-27.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries had formed a joint committee to
examine the obstacles obstructing navigation between them. He said
the committee would hold its first meeting in the first week of
December.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not give the date of the resumption of the
navigation.
</P>
<P>
River navigation along the Nile river between Wadi Halfa in
northern Sudan and the Aswan port in south Egypt is the only means
of water transport linking the two neighboring states. It was
suspended in 1992 due to the deterioration of relations between
the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971124.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-23 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi FM Welcomes Proposal on Debating UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed al-Sahhaf said today that his country welcomes a
proposal put forward by Kenya on the re-opening of a debate on
the U.N. sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference here this evening, Sahhaf also
welcomed suggestions put forward before the Security Council on
replacing the American U2 spy plane with another one from a
different country and a French proposal regarding options for
alternating reconnaissance planes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he revealed that the understanding reached between
Iraq and the U.N. stipulated that U.N. arms inspection teams
avoid getting close to locations considered as part and parcel of
Iraq's national sovereignty and security.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there were no banned weapons in Iraq and the
action of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
dismantling Iraqi weapons of mass destruction from 1993 until now
was mere "procrastination" in blocking the lifting of the
sanctions imposed on Iraq for its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions can not be lifted unless the weapons inspection
teams verify that Iraq has eliminated all its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. arms inspection teams have resumed their work in Iraq
after a Russian-brokered compromise eased the confrontation
between Iraq and the U.N. triggered by Iraqi expulsion of six
Americans in the UNSCOM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
